    songs: ["Beauty and the Beast","Rock-a-Bye Your Baby With a Dixie Melody","Why Do They All Take the Night Boat to Albany?","’N Everything"],
    performances: 388,
    synopsis: "At a time when it was not uncommon for musicals to be built around the talents of one individual, no shows were more vehicular than those created to spotlight the exuberant personality of “Mammy” singer Al Jolson. Though they had large casts, such extravaganzas as Robinson Crusoe, Jr. (1916), Sinbad, Bombo (1921), and Big Boy (1925) were virtually one-man shows. All the Jolson entertainments were presented by the Messrs. Shubert, directed by J. C. Huffman, had easily ignored books by Harold Atteridge, were full of interpolated songs, and — except for Bombo — played the Winter Garden (on Broadway between 50th and 51st Streets).\n\nIn Sinbad, in which the star wore his customary black-face makeup, Jolson appeared in ancient Bagdad as a comical chap named Inbad who poses as Sinbad the Sailor. Between adventures, he literally stopped the show to introduce his own musical specialties, including “Avalon” (added after the opening) and George Gershwin’s first hit, “Swanee” (added during the road tour).",
