    songs: ["I’m Just Wild About Harry","Love Will Find a Way","Bandana Days","If You’ve Never Been Vamped by a Brownskin","Jive Drill","Bitten by Love","Falling","City Called Heaven—Juba-lee","Bongo-Boola","Swanee Moon","Rhythm of America","It’s the Gown That Makes the Gal That Makes the Guy","You Can’t Overdo a Good Thing","My Day","Give It Love","Farewell with Love","Here ’Tis","Reminiscing","Love Will Find a Way."],
    performances: 504,
    synopsis: "Developed from a vaudeville sketch, Shuffle Along became the first successful musical written, directed, and acted by black people. Little money was spent on costumes or scenery, but white audiences were happy to travel a bit north of the theatre district to enjoy the show’s earthy humor, fast pacing, spirited dancing, and infectious rhythms. The plot is concerned with the race for mayor of Jimtown, in Dixieland, between the venal Steve Jenkins (Flournoy Miller) and the virtuous Harry Walton (Roger Matthews), about whom, we are repeatedly advised, everyone is just wild. Though Steve wins, Harry eventually has him and his equally corrupt police chief, Sam Peck (Aubrey Lyles), thrown out of office. During the run, Paul Robeson joined the cast briefly as a member of a vocal quartet, and Josephine Baker was added to the touring company as a chorus girl. There were three titular successors to Shuffle Along: Keep Shufflin’ (1928), Shuffle Along of 1933(1932), and another Shuffle Along (1952). All of them availeth not. New World OC.",
