    id: "take-a-chance",
    title: "Take A Chance",
    year: 1932,
    era: "early",
    type: "musical",
    openingDate: "1932-11-26",
    theatre: "Apollo Theatre",
    composer: "Richard A. Whiting, Nacio Herb Brown, Vincent Youmans",
    lyricist: "B. G. DeSylva",
    bookWriter: "B. G. DeSylva, Laurence Schwab, Sid Silvers Producers: Laurence Schwab & B. G. DeSylva",
    director: "Edgar MacGregor",
    choreographer: "Bobby Connolly",
    producer: "Laurence Schwab & B. G. DeSylva",
    notableCast: ["Jack Haley","Ethel Merman","Jack Whiting","Sid Silvers","June Knight","Mitzi Mayfair","Oscar Ragland","Robert Gleckler"],
    songs: ["Should I Be Sweet?","Turn Out the Lights","Rice ‘n’ Shine","You’re an Old Smoothe","Eadie Was a Lady"],
    performances: 243,
    synopsis: "In September 1932, a musical titled Humpty Dumpty began its tryout tour in Pittsburgh. It involved Lou Holtz, Ethel Merman, and Eddie Foy Jr. in what was basically a revue with songs and sketches dealing with incidents in American history. It was so poorly received that the show closed in five days. Within three weeks, however, the production was totally revised, partly recast (Holtz and Foy were replaced by Jack Whiting and Jack Haley), and had five new songs by Vincent Youmans. Retitled Take a Chance — to indicate something of the risks involved - the show was now an old-fashioned book musical concerned with a romance between the leading man and leading lady (Whiting and June Knight) who are appearing in a revue about American history called Humpty Dumpty. What turned it into a hit, though, were the comedy and specialty numbers, with Miss Merman given two show stoppers — “Rise ‘n’ Shine” and “Eadie Was a Lady” — that let her blast her way clear up to the second balcony. During the Broadway run, Haley and Sid Silvers were succeeded by the vaudeville team of Olsen and Johnson.",
