    producer: "John C. Wilson & Nat Goldstone",
    notableCast: ["Celeste Holm","David Brooks","Dooley Wilson","Joan McCracken","Richard Huey","Margaret Douglass","Mabel Taliaferro","Matt Briggs","Herbert Ross"],
    songs: ["When the Boys Come Home","Evelina","It Was Good Enough for Grandma","Sunday in Cicero Falls","I Got a Song",";",";"],
    performances: 654,
    synopsis: "Continuing the Americana spirit of Oklahoma!, Bloomer Girl was not only concerned with the introduction of bloomers during the Civil War, it also covered various aspects of the women’s reform movement and the struggle for civil rights. The action occurs in Cicero Falls, New York, in 1861, and covers the rebellion of Evelina Applegate (Celeste Holm) against her tyrannical father, a manufacturer of hoopskirts, who wants her to marry one of his salesmen. Evelina is so provoked that she joins her aunt, Amelia “Dolly” Bloomer (Margaret Douglass), in both her crusade for more practical clothing for women and in her abolitionist activities. Evelina’s convictions, however, do not prevent her from singing the romantic duet, “Rigth as the Rain,” with Jefferson Calhoun (David Brooks), a visiting Southern slaveholder, who is eventually won over to her cause. Bloomer Girl made a star of Celeste Holm (who was succeeded in her role by Nanette Fabray), and it was also noted for Agnes de Mille’s “Civil War Ballet,” depicting the anguish felt by women who must remain at home while their men are off fighting. The musical returned to New York for six weeks early in 1947.\n\nBroadway has also seen the following Civil War musicals: The Girl from Dixie (1903), Caroline (1923), My Maryland (1927), My Darlin’ Aida (1952), Maggie Flynn (1968), and Shenandoah (1975).\n\nBloomer Girl. Joan McCracken showing off her bloomers to Margaret Douglass and Celeste Holm. (Vandamm)",
