    songs: ["Give Your Heart a Chance to Sing","Doin’ the Old Yahoo Step","Molly O’Reilly","Who Hit Me?"],
    performances: 460,
    synopsis: "Billed as “An Intimate Musical Revue” (there were 21 in the cast), Lend an Ear was the first of 14 musicals to be directed and choreographed by Gower Champion. It also revealed the triple talents of writer Charles Gaynor, and it marked the Broadway debut of a squeaky-voiced, saucer-eyed blonde named Carol Channing. Initially presented seven years earlier in Pittsburgh, the youthful show came to New York after a successful engagement in Los Angeles. Among its satirical topics: psychoanalists; the influence of gossip columnists; a tourist-eye view of Santo Domingo; a third-rate opera company that must speak its lines because it cannot afford orchestral accompaniment; queens of the silent screen; and “The Gladiola Girl,” an encapsulated typical musical comedy of the mid-Twenties about flappers and lounge lizards on a Long Island estate where everyone dances “The Old Yahoo Step.”\n\nKiss Me, Kate. Alfred Drake taming his shrew Patricia Morison. (Eileen Darby)",
