    type: "musical",
    openingDate: "1950-02-02",
    closingDate: "1950-05-27",
    theatre: "46th Street Theatre",
    composer: "Morton Gould",
    lyricist: "Dorothy Fields",
    bookWriter: "Herbert Fields, Dorothy Fields, and Rouben Mamoulian",
    director: "Rouben Mamoulian",
    producer: "The Theatre Guild in association with Anthony Brady Farrell",
    songs: ["A Girl with a Flame","That’s What I Told Him Last Night","I Like It Here","That’s My Fella","A Cow and a Plough and a Frau","Nothin’ for Nothin’","He Will Tonight","Don’t Talk","Plantation in Philadelphia","You Kissed Me","I’ll Never Learn","There Must Be Something Better Than Love","She’s Exciting","Mister Washington! Uncle George"],
    performances: 134,
    funFact: "The Philadelphia Playbill cover, above right, features Arthur Hill, Viveca Lindfors (before she was fired), Cook, and Ronny Graham.",
    synopsis: "However, the critics loved her, and apparently audiences did, too. She just never got lucky with the right Broadway musical, and Love Life, Arms and the Girl, Make a Wish (1951), and Mr. President (1962) were all financial failures with relatively brief Broadway runs. Today, Fabray is most likely remembered by musical comedy lovers as one of the quartet who introduced Howard Dietz and Arthur Schwartz’s standard “That’s Entertainment” in MGM’s classic 1953 film musical The Band Wagon. But despite her sparkling presence in a hit movie, she never again had the opportunity to shine in Hollywood.\n\nIn Arms and the Girl, Fabray played the role of Jo Kirkland, a sort of Joan of Arc by way of Lucy Ricardo. In her first song (“A Girl with a Flame”), we discover Jo wants to help the colonies win independence. But despite good intentions, wacky Jo bungles everything. When she meets Hessian soldier Franz (Georges Guetary), who has deserted the British Army in order to help the American cause, she believes he’s a spy. And she thinks that Colonel Mortimer Sherwood (John Conte), one of George Washington’s most trusted and devoted followers, is also a spy. And, sure enough, when Jo sets out to destroy a bridge, she blows up the wrong one. Finally, General Washington himself (Arthur Vinton) has to get involved and plead with her to stop meddling.\n\nThe musical, and The Pursuit of Happiness, the play upon which it was based, made much of the Colonial custom of “bundling” (on cold winter nights, an unmarried man and woman could share a bed for company and for warmth, as long as the bed was divided by a saw-toothed wooden board). In her quest to track down imaginary spies, Jo bundles with both Franz and Sherwood.\n\nBrooks Atkinson in the New York Times said the musical was a “conventional operetta. . . . In craftsmanship and point of view it is closer to The Student Prince,” and he felt Rouben Mamoulian’s direction did little to set aright “the stereotypes of operetta” which permeated the production (operettas were a particular bugaboo of Atkinson’s, and he pounced on musicals that leaned in that direction). But he liked the evocative scenery and costumes by Horace Armistead and Audre, respectively, and said Michael Kidd’s choreography was joyous (there were two major dances in the musical, “That’s My Fella” and “Plantation in Philadelphia”). And he praised the “clowning exuberance” of Pearl Bailey’s Connecticut (Bailey played an escaped slave who assumes the name of whatever colony she is in), noting she brought “considerable useful strutting” to the proceedings. (Incidentally, the title of “Plantation in Philadelphia” derives from geographically challenged Connecticut’s confusion about the locations of VA and PA.) Robert Garland in the Journal-American said the musical should be retitled Connecticut in honor of Pearl Bailey, although Howard Barnes in the New York Herald-Tribune noted that Connecticut (a new character invented for the musical) and her songs had “little or no relation to” the plot. Overall, Barnes found the new musical “ponderous” and “dull” as well as “wordy, repetitious and poorly paced”; Richard Watts in the New York Post said the evening was “not very exciting” and “surprisingly mild,” and hinted at old-fashioned operetta in his reference to the musical’s “merry villagers”; and William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun complained that the book “has been pulled apart too often and stitched together like a rearranged patchwork quilt.”\n\nWatts said Morton Gould’s score wasn’t “particularly interesting,” and noted Bailey’s “humorous brilliance” made her “fairly ordinary songs seem witty and charming.” Hawkins felt there was “rarely a song lilting enough to win you,” but John Chapman in the Daily News said the music was in the “sweet and fruity Gould style.” Barnes found the score “engaging,” and Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror predicted that “several” songs in the score were “Hit Parade candidates” (he had also wrongly predicted that songs in Happy as Larry were destined for the Hit Parade). As for Gould, Arms and the Girl was his second and final Broadway musical (Billion Dollar Baby [1945] was also a failure, running for 220 performances).\n\nIt appears Mamoulian did all he could to enliven the somewhat slow-moving plot and the decidedly lackluster score. General Washington made his appearance on a magnificent white steed; when Jo blows up a bridge, the stage was awash in fish; and another scene depicted a snow storm. Further, in preparing for a johnnycake party, Jo performs a Colonial version of a strip tease; and the bundling scene with Jo, Franz, and then later with Sherwood was, according to Chapman, “so fast and funny in its movement” that he was reminded of a Mack Sennett movie.\n\nDecca released the cast album (ten-inch LP # DL-5200), which included eight songs (“A Girl with a Flame,” “That’s What I Told Him Last Night,” “I Like It Here,” “That’s My Fella,” “A Cow and a Plough and a Frau,” “No",
