    composer: "John Mundy",
    lyricist: "Edward Eager",
    bookWriter: "Edward Eager and Alfred Drake",
    director: "Alfred Drake",
    choreographer: "Hanya Holm",
    producer: "Dorothy Willard and Thomas Hammond",
    songs: ["March of the Guards","The Ladies’ Opinion","You’ve Stolen My Heart","The Liar’s Song","Supper Trio","Truth","Lackaday","Stop Holding Me Back","What’s in a Name","Women’s Work","Spring","Stomachs and Stomachs","A Jewel of a Duel","Out of Sight, Out of Mind","A Plot to Catch a Man In","Funeral March","’Twill Never Be the Same"],
    performances: 12,
    synopsis: "“A New Musical Comedy” (tryout); “A Musical Version of The Liar” (New York) Theatre: Broadhurst Theatre Opening Date: May 18, 1950; Closing Date: May 27, 1950\n\nThe plot promised a merry evening of romantic misadventures, but the critics felt the libretto was lackluster and the leading man somewhat disappointing.\n\nRichard Watts in the New York Post found the evening a “tedious and self-conscious antic . . . a very sedate jest”; Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror said the show was “pedestrian and dull . . . an amazing demonstration of how a number of outstanding talents can combine to small purpose”; John Chapman in the Daily News remarked that the musical was “laggard . . . awfully long stretches of unexciting plot and the net effect is squashy rather than bouncy”; and L.F. (Lewis Funke) in the New York Times felt the “good people” involved with the production were unable to add the “variety” needed for this “Venetian vignette,” an evening that demanded ”spontaneity, gusto, bounce and lustiness.” William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun noted the show began well, but by intermission suffered “serious dislocations. The book’s bridges collapse, and the show’s exuberance falls into the canal.” Robert Garland in the New York Journal-American felt the musical occasionally pulled itself together to offer an “entertaining” evening, but noted the production needed to “be more continuously entertaining than it is.”\n\nAs for the songs, Hawkins praised Eager’s “fascinating” and “sparkling and insouciant” lyrics and Mundy’s score, which “should delight fans of W. Mozart and A. Sullivan”; he said the music was “characterized by a delicate impertinence,” and singled out six songs: “Out of Sight, Out of Mind,” “Lackaday,” “Women’s Work,” “March of the Guards,” “Truth,” and the cleverly titled “A Plot to Catch a Man In.” The Times also compared some of the songs to Gilbert and Sullivan, and singled out “You’ve Stolen My Heart,” “Lackaday,” and “Out of Sight, Out of Mind.” Watts also compared the lyrics to Gilbert’s, and said the score was “pleasant.” Chapman predicted “Lackaday” would be the show’s hit song; and Otis T. Guernsey in the New York Herald Tribune thought the score contained “pleasant interludes,” especially “Truth,” “Women’s Work,” and “Lackaday.” (The music for “Women’s Work” was composed by Lehman Engel, the show’s musical director.) Watts felt William Eythe was “competent enough,” but lacked “the proper romantic style and humorous flourish . . . he strives manfully to fabricate an air of satirical bravado that is not forthcoming”; the Times said he fell short of the “kind of powerful authenticity that could dominate the stage and make a theatre glow”; and Garland felt he was “not too well adapted” for the role but “did well enough.” However, Chapman found him “gay and personable,” and Coleman said he was “dynamic and appealing.” Hawkins felt Eythe would have conquered the part “in a little more time” because he had “the flourish, the stamina and the charm” necessary for the title role (when original lead Dennis Harrison was dismissed, Eythe assumed the role during the Philadelphia tryout). But Hawkins noted by evening’s end Eythe (and the show) suffered from “sheer exhaustion,” and he concluded Eythe’s “cocky banter” and “zany range” suggested “Carol Channing doing an imitation of Ronald Coleman.” (Incidentally, Eythe was one of the coproducers of the hit 1948 revue Lend an Ear, which provided Channing with her breakthrough role.) It appears Eythe may have had a weak singing voice. It’s notable that despite playing the leading role, his character wasn’t given a single solo number, and that he shared his songs with other characters or with the chorus. During the tryout, “The Liar’s Song” and “Out of Sight, Out of Mind” were solos for Dennis Harrison, but when Eythe replaced him, the first number became a duet for Eythe and Joshua Shelley, and the latter added a chorus to accompany Eythe. Moreover, later in the year Eythe was one of the leads in Cole Porter’s Out of This World, and here he didn’t sing a note. During the musical’s tryout, he and Priscilla Gillette introduced the now-standard “From This Moment On,” but the song was dropped prior to New York (by some accounts, because the song was more than Eythe could handle).\n\nAs mentioned, Eythe replaced Dennis Harrison during the tryout of The Liar (three photographs from the production accompany the musical’s entry on page 108 of Theatre World Season 1949–1950; two small photos identify the performers, but the third, and larger, photo doesn’t; it seems that the handsome performer wearing a vest and billowing white shirt is Harrison). Director Norris Houghton was also replaced, by co-librettist Alfred Drake. (Between the firing of Harrison and the hiring of Eythe, Drake himself may have played the leading role for a few tryout performances.) During the tryout, the following songs were deleted: “Now Sleeps the Crimson Petal,” “Steal Me,” “Drink, D",
