    synopsis: "Sketches and Lyrics: Mike Stewart Music: Leo Schumer, Shelley Mowell, James Reed Lawlor, Bernice Kroll, and Irma Jurist Direction: Edward Reveaux; Producers: David Heilweil and Derrick Lynn-Thomas in association with Madeline Capp and Greer Johnson; Choreography: Nelle Fisher (Jerry Ross, Associate Choreographer); Scenery, Costumes, and Lighting: William Riva; Musical Direction: James Reed Lawlor Cast: Robert H. Baron, Peter Conlow, Kate Friedlich, Lee Goodman, Cris Goodyear, Dorothy Greener, Barbara Hamilton, James Harwood, Bob Herget, James Jewell, Christine Karner, Bill Newey, Jet MacDonald, Frank Reynolds, Jean Sincere, Flori Waren, Jane White The revue was presented in two acts.\n\nSketches and Musical Numbers Act One: “What’s a Show” (music by Shelley Mowell) (Ringmaster: James Jewell; Acrobat: Kate Friedlich; Clown: Dorothy Greener; Equestrienne: Flori Waren; Romeo: Frank Reynolds; Juliet: Jean Sincere; Sweethearts: Christine Karner and Bob Herget; Girl with Hat: Barbara Hamilton; Riveter: James Harwood; Texan: Lee Goodman; Kid: Cris Goodyear; Keystone Cop: Peter Conlow; Girl with Shoulders: Jane White); “M.G.M.” (Dorothy Greener); “Sign Here” (music by Leo Schumer) (Wife: Jean Sincere; Husband: James Harwood; Owner: Lee Goodman; Rufus McBain: Frank Reynolds; McBain Sisters: Kate Friedlich and Christine Karner; Boyfriends: Peter Conlow and Bob Herget; Beth: Flori Waren); “Then I’m Yours” (music by Leo Schumer) (Jet MacDonald, James Jewell); “All about Bambi” (Part One): A—Dressing Room (Bambi: Barbara Hamilton; Girl: Dorothy Greener); B—The Wages of Sin (1925) (music by James Reed Lawlor) (Waiter: Robert H. Baron; Boy: Frank Reynolds; Bunny Girl: Christine Karner; Nell’s Date: Bob Herget; Little Nell: Kate Friedlich; Nell’s Father: James Harwood; Nell’s Mother: Flori Waren; Bambi: Barbara Hamilton); “N.Y.C.” (music by Leo Schumer) (Girl: Jean Sincere; Scarecrow: Peter Conlow); “Magic in the Woods” (Author: Lee Goodman); “Haven’t We Met Before?” (music by Irma Jurist) (The Producer: James Harwood; First Lady: Jane White; Second Lady: Jean Sincere; Visitor: Barbara Hamilton); “What a Way to Make a Living” (music by Leo Schumer) (Jet MacDonald and Lee Goodman); “All about Bambi” (Part Two): A—Dressing Room (Bambi: Barbara Hamilton; Girl: Dorothy Greener); B—Frivolity Frolics (1930) (music by Leo Schumer) (Singer: James Harwood; Girls: Kate Friedlich, Christine Karner, Flori Waren, Jet MacDonald, Jean Sincere; Stripper: Jane White; Bambi: Barbara Hamilton) Act Two: “Catch Me If You Can” (music by Shelley Mowell) (The Girl: Jet MacDonald; The Men: Peter Conlow, Bob Herget, Frank Reynolds); “You’re Only Young Once or Twice” (music by Bernice Kroll) (Girl: Christine Karner; Boy: James Jewell); “All about Bambi” (Part Three): A—The Stage (Bambi: Barbara Hamilton; Girl: Dorothy Greener; Stage Manager: Bob Herget; Actor: Lee Goodman); B—Love on Shrove Tuesday (1939) (Diantha: Barbara Hamilton; Maid: Dorothy Greener; Gregory: Lee Goodman; Butler: James Harwood); “The Light Fantastic” (music by James Reed Lawlor) (The Witch: Flori Waren; Narrator: James Harwood); “Grace Fogarty” (Dorothy Greener); “Someone” (music by Shelley Mowell) (Jane White; danced by Kate Friedlich and Bob Herget); “All about Bambi” (Part Four): A—Dressing Room (Actor: Lee Goodman; Girl: Dorothy Greener; Stage Manager: James Jewell); B—Two Hearts in Gypsy Time (1951) (music by Shelley Mowell) (Dancer: Peter Conlow; Flower Girl: Kate Friedlich; Innkeeper: James Harwood; Girls: Jean Sincere, Jane White, Christine Karner, Flori Waren; Waiters and Students: Cris Goodyear, Bill Newey, James Jewell, Robert H. Baron; Rupert: Frank Reynolds; Private Stanislaus: Leo Goodman; Zasa: Dorothy Greener; Gypsy: Barbara Hamilton); Finale (Company) If the lavish Bless You All was one of the biggest and most expensive revues of its era, Razzle Dazzle was the tiniest. The intimate show of seventeen cast members and three musicians (two pianists and a percussionist) was the fourth production to play at the recently opened Arena in the Edison Hotel. The theatrical space had once been the hotel’s ballroom, and was now offering modest productions in theatre-in-the-round fashion (earlier in the season, the revivals of Gian-Carlo Menotti’s The Medium and The Telephone had played there). The venue was small and more in the nature of an Off-Broadway theatre (Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times described the stage as the size of a pocket handkerchief). As The Arena, the theatre didn’t last long, but in 1970 it reopened as the Edison Theatre, and for twenty years presented a number of Off-Broadway and Middle-Broadway productions, both plays and musicals (including Kurt Vonnegut’s 1970 play Happy Birthday, Wanda June, the 1971 revival of Johnny Johnson, and the theatre’s longest-running tenant, the 1972 musical revue Dont Bother Me, I Cant Cope).\n\nBigger wasn’t better for Bless You All, and modest production values and mild material didn’t help Razzle Dazzle: it received",
