    funFact: "This time, it was Atkinson who gave the show its best review; otherwise, the notices were mixed.",
    synopsis: "There were a couple of awkwardly introduced songs, but they were so pleasant one didn’t mind. Despite the summertime setting, the score’s loveliest song was “After All, It’s Spring” (the characters quickly recall events of the recent spring as an excuse to sing it) and the ragtime-inflected “OO-OOO-OOO, What You Do to Me” is a number George Crooper heard in the Ziegfeld Follies (“It went like this,” George says, and then he proceeds to sing it).\n\nPerhaps the highlight of the score was “I Could Get Married Today” for Willie, Genesis, and the latter’s father, Mr. Genesis. The trio looks at the difference between Willie, who sings that marriage must be delayed until the prospective husband is financially secure, and Mr. Genesis, who notes that money didn’t stop him from taking a bride.\n\nThe critics were generally kind to the mild little musical, but the less-than-rave reviews, coupled with the lack of a star name and a hit song, forced the musical to close at a loss after five months. Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times praised the “touching and uproarious portrait” of adolescence, and liked the “taste, sympathy and relish” found in the “high standard” of Sally Benson’s book; he didn’t think the score was up to the libretto, but quickly noted a few of the songs were “lively and joyous” and full of “rousing spirit”; Richard Watts in the New York Post said the evening was “vastly agreeable and appealing” in its unpretentiousness and “honestly youthful charm”; and Marie Torre in the New York World-Telegram and Sun found the show “mildly pleasant” and “mildly diverting.”\n\nBut Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror found the book “paper-thin” and the score “pleasant though undistinguished”; Robert Garland in the New York Journal-American said Willie and Lola were “tiresome” characters, the score “lively” but “without real distinction,” and with the choice of taking or leaving the musical, he would leave it; Otis L. Guernsey in the New York Herald Tribune wrote that the “pale ice cream musical” was “flimsy satire, even for a summer show” (but there were “a few good tunes”); and John Chapman in the Daily News said that “if it only had some music it would be quite a nice show.”\n\nThe cast album was released by RCA Victor (LP # LOC-1033), and a CD was issued by RCA Masterworks Broadway (# 88725-42775-2). Another CD edition of the score (which was paired with the original cast recording of High Button Shoes) was released by Sepia (# 1048) and includes a bonus track of a pop rendition of “OO-OOO-OOO, What You Do to Me!” by Art Mooney. The script of the musical was published in softcover by Samuel French in 1954.\n\nSeventeen was first adapted for the stage in 1918 by Hugh Stanislaus Stange and Stannard Mears; Gregory Kelly was Willie and Rosemary’s Baby’s future Oscar-winner Ruth Gordon was Lola. Also in the cast was Judith Lowry (Mrs. Baxter), who was still acting more than a half century later as an occasional fixture in television sitcoms (in the Mary Tyler Moore Show spinoff Phyllis she played Mother Dexter). A 1940 film version of the novel starred Jackie Cooper (Willie) and Betty Field (Lola).\n\nSeventeen wasn’t the first musical adaptation of the material. Hello, Lola! opened at the Eltinge Theatre on January 12, 1926, for forty-seven performances; the book and lyrics were by Dorothy Donnelly, and the music by William B. Kernel; Richard Keene was Willie, and Edythe Baker played the title role.\n\nKenneth Nelson was a frequent visitor to Broadway and the West End, but his two greatest successes were Off-Broadway. He created the role of The Boy (Matt) in the original 1960 production of Tom Jones and Harvey Schmidt’s The Fantasticks and introduced such songs as “Soon It’s Gonna Rain,” “I Can See It,” and “They Were You.” In 1968, he created the role of the poisonous party giver Michael in Mart Crowley’s drama The Boys in the Band, and in 1970 reprised the role for the film version.\n\nAfter Seventeen, Ellen McCown created just one more role in a Broadway musical when she replaced Zeme North during the tryout of Frank Loesser’s Greenwillow (1960) and introduced the haunting “Faraway Boy,” one of the finest Broadway songs of the era.\n\nAt the end of the 1950s, Peter Conlow returned to the small-town America of the early 1900s with Take Me Along (1959), another musical about a moonstruck teenaged boy in love (Conlow sang “Wint’s Song,” a come-hither, almost throwaway number in which he invited his best friend to join him in a visit to a local brothel).\n\nSeventeen was the only Broadway score by the team of Kim Gannon and Walter Kent. The musical didn’t produce any popular standards, but they wrote one of the most enduring of all holiday songs with their sweet and poignant “I’ll Be Home for Christmas.”\n\nThe George Crooper character seems to have managed an organized calendar. He finished his school year at Yale, saw the opening night performance of the Ziegfeld Follies in New York (it opened on July 7, 1907), spent some time in Scra",
