    performances: 281,
    synopsis: "Sketches and Lyrics: Betty Comden and Adolph Green, and Nat Hiken and William Friedberg Lyrics: Betty Comden and Adolph Green Music: Jule Styne Direction: Abe Burrows; Producer: Arthur Lesser; Choreography: Ted Cappy; Scenery and Lighting: Howard Bay; Costumes: Joan Personette; Musical Direction: Herbert Greene Cast: Bert Lahr, Dolores Gray, Elliott Reid, Colette Marchand, J. C. McCord, Stanley Prager, Kathryne Mylorie, Alan LeRoy, Patricia Tobin, Robert Gallagher, Richard Gray, Larry Laurence, Arthur Rubin, Walter Kelvin, Frank Reynolds, Gordon Hamilton, Bob Emmett, Jeannette Aquilina, Vera Lee, Gloria Danyl, Margery Beddow, Jane Mason, Richard Hamilton; Singers: Marion Lauer, Leila Martin, Beverly McFadden, Leslie Parry, Peggy Reiss, Carol Sawyer, Geraldine Sloan, Joanne Spiller, Julie Williams, John Allen, Arthur Arney, Fred Bryan, Buford Jasper, Walter Kelvin, John Raye, Arthur Rubin; Dancers: Jeannette Aquilina, Margery Beddow, Betty Buday, Gloria Danyl, Dorothy Etheridge, Doris Goodwin, Vera Lee, Jane Mason, Bob Emmett, Jerry Fries, John Kelly, Paul Lyday, Victor Reilley, Frank Reynolds; Show Girls: Gregg Evans, Rosemary Kittelton, Dell Parker, Mira Stefan, Jeanne Tyler, Charlotte Van Lein The revue was presented in two acts.\n\nSketches and Musical Numbers Act One: “Show Train” (Conductors: Stanley Prager, Robert Gallagher, Larry Laurence, Arthur Rubin, Walter Kelvin, Ensemble); “Hold Me Tight” (aka “Hold Me, Hold Me, Hold Me”) (First Suitor: Frank Reynolds; Second Suitor: John Kelly; Third Suitor: Bob Emmett; Maid: Jeannette Aquilina; The Girl: Dolores Gray); “Highlights from the World of Sports” (Producer: Alan LeRoy; Announcer: Elliott Reid; Cameramen: Richard Gray, Robert Gallagher; Lefty Hogan: Bert Lahr); “East River Hoe Down” (aka “And Here She Comes Now”) (J. C. McCord, Vera Lee, Ensemble); “There Never Was a Baby Like My Baby” (Wife: Dolores Gray; Husband: Elliott Reid; danced by J. C. McCord; assisted by Gloria Danyl, Margery Beddow, Jane Mason, John Kelly, and Frank Reynolds); “Space Brigade” (Hodgkins: Richard Gray; Hotchkiss: Larry Laurence; Hitchcock: Robert Gallagher; Captain Universe: Bert Lahr; Higgins: Stanley Prager; Radio Voice: Walter Kelvin; Queen Chlorophyl: Kathryn Mylorie; Denizens of Venus: Arthur Arney, John Raye, Victor Reilly, Buford Jasper, Victor Reilley); “If You Hadn’t, But You Did” (aka “If”) (The Girl: Dolores Gray; The Other Woman: Gloria Danyl; The Man: Bob Emmett); “The Clown” (Bert Lahr; assisted by Vera Lee, Gloria Danyl, Dell Parker, and Mira Stefan); “The Guide Book” (Three Urchins: Frank Reynolds, Victor Reilley, John Kelly; The Girl: Colette Marchand; The Lovers: Paul Lyday, Betty Buday; Traveler: Bob Emmett; The American: J. C. McCord; assisted by Jane Mason, Jeannette Aquilina, Margery Beddow, and Jerry Fries); “Here’s What You Said” (monologue written and performed by Elliott Reid); “Catch Our Act” (aka “Vaudeville Ain’t Dead”) (Bert Lahr, Dolores Gray); “At the Met” (Siegfried: Bert Lahr; Brunnhilde: Dolores Gray; The Dragon: Stanley Prager; danced by Colette Marchand; Ensemble) Act Two: “Everlasting” (Kathryn Mylorie, Fred Bryan; danced by Dorothy Etheridge and Jerry Fries; Ensemble); “Schneider’s Miracle” (by Nat Hiken and William Friedberg) (Schneider: Bert Lahr; Mrs. Higgleston: Patricia Tobin; Piper: Stanley Prager; Miss Flaherty: Kathryn Mylorie; Inspector: Robert Gallagher; Man on Bench: Alan LeRoy; Little Girl: Jeannette Aquilina; Policeman: Richard Gray; Passers-by: John Allen, Leila Martin, Frank Reynolds, Walter Kelvin); “Give a Little, Get a Little Love” (Dolores Gray, Ensemble); “Didy Dolls” (Bert Lahr, Dell Parker, Mira Stefan, Charlotte Van Lein, Gregg Evans, Rosemary Kittelton, Jeanne Tyler, Vera Lee; Voice: Arthur Rubin; “Triangle” (1)—Hubby: Elliott Reid; Wifey: Dolores Gray; Lovey: Bert Lahr; (2)—Husband: Elliott Reid; Wife: Dolores Gray; Close Friend: Bert Lahr; (3)—He: Elliott Reid; She: Dolores Gray; Him: Bert Lahr); “Dog Show” (choreographed by Ruthanna Boris) (Judge: Bob Emmett; Russian Wolfhounds: Gregg Evans, Rosemary Kittelton, Dell Parker, Mira Stefan, Jeanne Tyler, Charlotte Van Lein; Their Trainer: Jerry Fries; Pekingese: Dorothy Etheridge; Her Trainer: Paul Lyday; Cocker Spaniels: Gloria Danyl, Jane Mason; Their Trainer: Victor Reilley; Dalmatians: Betty Buday, Doris Goodwin; Their Trainer: John Kelly; French Poodle: Colette Marchand; Her Manager: Gordon Hamilton); “How Will He Know?” (Mr. Murdock: Bert Lahr; Miss Travers: Dolores Gray); Finale (Bert Lahr, Dolores Gray, Colette Marchand, Company) Despite lyrics and sketches by Betty Comden and Adolph Green, music by Jule Styne, and stellar performances by veteran Bert Lahr and relative newcomer Dolores Gray, Two on the Aisle was another of the era’s revues to close in the red. But it did better than most: it played for almost three hundred performances, toured briefly with its stars, and left behind a cast album.\n\nThe satiric targets were typical of the period: television (“",
