    director: "Guthrie McClintic",
    producer: "The New York City Theatre Company (George Schaefer, Artistic Director) (A Guthrie McClintic Production)",
    performances: 30,
    synopsis: "Play: Clemence Dane Music: Richard Addinsell Direction: Guthrie McClintic; Producer: The New York City Theatre Company (George Schaefer, Artistic Director) (A Guthrie McClintic Production); Scenery: Raymond Sovey (from designs by James Reynolds); Costumes: Noel Taylor (Judith Anderson’s costumes by Valentina); Lighting: Uncredited; Musical Direction: Macklin Marrow Cast: Robert Brown (A Boy), Robert Harrison (A Shadow of Death), Judith Anderson (A Woman), Melville Ruick (A Man), Marian Seldes (A Close Friend); Friends of the Woman: Ethel (Barrymore) Colt, Richard Barbee, June Jollie, James Noble, Lita Dal Porto, Stephen Reese, Muriel Rahn, James Bronson, Barbara Torrance, Gerry Jedd, Phoebe MacKaye, Peter Brandon, Bill Krach, Jacqueline deWit; Muriel Rahn (An Entertainer); Musical Personnel: Macklin Marrow (Orchestra Leader), George Bauer and Jack Eisenberg (Duo Pianists), Muriel Rahn (Singer for the Woman), Beverly Hosier (Singer for River Music), Thomas Motto (Singer for the Boy) The play with music was presented in three acts.\n\nThe programs for the 1934 and 1952 productions didn’t list musical numbers; the list below reflects the songs as presented in the published script.\n\nThe characters were given generic names (A Man, A Woman, etc.), and the entire work was spoken in rhymed couplets. In a preface to the published script in 1934, the authors said their “experiment” was to “express real emotion” in “doggerel, which is the slang of poetry.” Further, background music was to be used to complement the action and to accompany much of the rhymed dialogue. At times offstage performers would give their singing voices to the leading players, and for party scenes an entertainer performed.\n\nThe plot dealt with a seventeen-year-old poet (played by Robert Brown) who commits suicide in 1770 (the character was based on real-life poet Thomas Chatterton). Since he died young and never came of age, he asks Death (Robert Harrison) for another chance at life in order to experience love. His wish is granted, and soon the ethereal young man finds himself in the London of the twentieth century, not as a poet but as a Noel Coward-type who pens songs for revues and musicals (“a kind of educated Pal Joey,” commented John Chapman in the Daily News). Like Joey, he becomes involved with a rich woman (Judith Anderson); their affair burns hot, but soon her neurotic jealousy, general unpleasantness, and dependence on the bottle become too much. The young man decides he’s had enough of life, and now that he’s reached manhood and experienced love, he’s more than ready to return to the afterlife.\n\nWhile most of the critics weren’t impressed with the play, they complimented the revival’s spare-no-expense production. Guthrie McClintic was on hand to direct, and there was lovely scenery (based on the ivory-and-gold-colored designs used in the original production), lavish costumes, and a tinkling orchestra with superb singers. But the play itself was dreary and pretentious.\n\nBrooks Atkinson in the New York Times liked Addinsell’s “exquisite” and “shimmering” music, but felt Dane’s words were too “trivial” to capture the story’s essential “loveliness” and “melancholy.” Walter Kerr praised the “thoroughly professional elegance” of McClintic’s direction, but the play itself was a “little horror” and he warned his readers that nothing could prepare them “for the numbing effect of an entire evening spent listening to choppy, cryptic, and endlessly repetitious” rhymed dialogue that equaled the “artistic level of the Burma Shave ads.” John McClain in the New York Journal-American liked the “uniformly charming music” that appropriately provided a background mood for the story and was used in a manner quite similar to the music in The Third Man; but he didn’t like the use of “oblique” verse to tell the story. Richard Watts in the New York Post didn’t find the work “satisfactory or distinguished”; it was shallow and Dane’s rhymed dialogue was “frequently intolerable” (he described Addinsell’s score as “ominous”).\n\nWilliam Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun found the revival a “triumph,” and for him the rhyme scheme employed “mature slang” in a repetitious and fragmentary fashion that echoed “actual conversation.” Chapman had enjoyed the original 1934 production, but now found the work somewhat “callow and self-conscious” and noted that the score had once seemed “modern” but “now sounded like stuff from a bygone jazz age.” He mentioned that the offstage orchestra and singers were sometimes hard to understand in the cavernous theatre, and this sentiment was echoed by Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror, who felt the delicate nature of the proceedings was lost in the large house and would have been better served in a smaller theatrical venue.\n\nAs for Judith Anderson, Atkinson praised her “vital, skillful and imaginative” performance, and Watts said her “sheer dramatic power” was “vivid and interesting” and in some ways made her character the c",
