    songs: ["Italy","Old-Fashioned Mothers","Skip the Build-Up","Nothing at All","Walk Like a Sailor","Headin’ for the Bottom Blues","Nothing Can Replace a Man","Here’s to Dear Old Us","His and Hers","La Festa","Ready Cash","Kiss Me and Kill Me with Love","Honeymoon","The Villain Always Gets It","The Code","Eleven O’clock Song","mediocrity"],
    performances: 176,
    synopsis: "The plot centered on Wynne (Jane Kean) and Elsey (Betty Kean), the former a movie star and the latter her standin. Wynne’s latest movie is being filmed on location in Italy, and although she’s secretly married to naval officer Bill Kelley (Mark Dawson), she hopes the two of them can spend some time together. Two of Elsey’s sailor pals Spud and Dinky (yes, Spud and Dinky), played by Gabriel Dell and Lew Parker, smuggle Wynne (in fighter-pilot drag) aboard the USS Alamo (no comment), where Bill is stationed and which is conveniently anchored close to where Wynne’s movie is being made. The plot’s stark realism then took the audience to Morocco where Bill’s former flame Lucia (Betty George) tries unsuccessfully to implicate him in an espionage plot.\n\nWalter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune noted that “some of us” had hoped for the return of the old-fashioned musical, but after seeing Ankles Aweigh “some of us ought to be shot.” He reported the humor was on the level of someone saying “Lollobrigida is falling down”; that one’s shipboard quarters are the “bunk”; and that a rum-ridden drunk is “Rummy-o and Juliet.” Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times said the evening was a “succession of show-shop clichés,” and while it was difficult to come across a Broadway musical that had “no talent,” Ankles Aweigh offered a “certain fascination” in that respect because the sisters Kean were “hackneyed performers with the mannerisms of small-time vaudeville,” the music was “destitute of originality,” the lyrics were “mechanical,” and the jokes flew past the footlights like “dum-dum bullets.”\n\nJohn McClain in the New York Journal-American said the show’s title was the “tip-off,” for here was a musical with a plot that defied “definition”; the evening was “banal” and “corny,” and its only “high point” was the all-male dance number “The Code.” Richard Watts in the New York Post noted that anyone who went to a show called Ankles Aweigh had “only himself to blame.” He too noted the jokes ran to the level of the question, “How did you get to Morocco?” and the answer, “I changed at Canal Street.” And Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror called the “vintage vehicle” a “shoddy frolic” with a “pedestrian” score.\n\nJohn Chapman in the Daily News was a bit kinder in his assessment of the new musical, but even he admitted the plot was a “podgehodge—which is a scrambled hodgepodge” and noted the jokes were “elderly” and the score “merely serviceable.” William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun said the show belonged to another era, and with one or two other critics noted that late in the second act there was an off-the-wall explanation that the show was really a “satire.” But this “afterthought” was far “too late.”\n\nThe original cast album was released by Decca (LP # DL-9025), which proclaimed that Betty and Jane Kean were “the funniest pair of girls in the Western Hemisphere”; the album was later issued on CD by Decca Broadway (# B0002673-02).\n\nDuring the tryout, Howard Hoyt, Reginald Hammerstein, and Fred F. Finklehoffe were the credited producers, but by the New York opening all three were no longer cited and instead Anthony B. Farrell was listed as the sole producer. Sonny Tufts was replaced by Mark Dawson.\n\nAbout midway into the Broadway run, Jane Kean and Thelma Carpenter (Chipolata) left the production and were replaced by Georgia Reed and Vivian Dandridge, respectively. Carpenter was the lead singer for “Headin’ for the Bottom Blues,” but for the cast album Betty George (who played Lucia) performed the number.\n\nPerhaps the most surprising moment in the history of Ankles Aweigh occurred when it received an out-of-the-clear-blue-sky revival at the Goodspeed Opera House in East Haddam, Connecticut, on July 13, 1988. The book was revised by Charles Busch, and the sisters Elsey and Wynne became Lorraine and Gloria (played by D’Jamin Bartlett and Monica Carr). Mark McGrath was Bill, and Spud and Dinky (yes, Spud and Dinky) were played by Bobby Clark and Ken Lundie. Three songs from the original production were dropped (“An Old-Fashioned Mother,” “The Villain Always Gets It,” and “The Code”), a first-act finale titled “The Chase” was added, and “I Can Dream, Can’t I?” was interpolated from the 1938 Broadway musical Right This Way (lyric by Irving Kahal, music by Sammy Fain), which ran for two weeks and offered two standards (“I Can Dream, Can’t I?” and “I’ll Be Seeing You”).\n\nAnkles Aweigh was a reunion of sorts for lyricist Dan Shapiro and book writers Guy Bolton and Eddie Davis, all of whom had collaborated on the 1944 hit musical Follow the Girls. Perhaps Ankles Aweigh’s Spud and Dinky were a subtle homage (and a subtle sequel) to the earlier musical’s sailor-characters Goofy, Spud, and Dinky.\n\nA special word about Michael King, one of the musical’s chorus singers, who throughout the decade was also billed as Mike King and John Michael King. His father was operetta and musical comedy star Dennis King, who appeared in Rudol",
