    funFact: "Rodgers and Hammerstein supplied the entire $250,000 cost, and Feuer and Martin were promised twenty percent of the ultimately nonexistent profits.",
    synopsis: "Although the musical included a couple of second-drawer numbers (such as “Thinkin’” and “How Long?”), Rodgers’s score is richly melodic and Hammerstein’s lyrics are finely crafted. With its expansive melody and its knowing and introspective lyric, the opening number “All Kinds of People” introduces Doc and his philosophy of life, and was quickly followed by “The Tide Pool” and “A Lopsided Bus,” both of which reflected the shaky and ramshackle natures of fish and man. The jaunty if bittersweet “The Man I Used to Be” was another reflective number for Doc, and while he sang his alter-ego (Don Weissmuller) danced; Suzy’s “Everybody’s Got a Home but Me” was a haunting depiction of her loneliness; and there were two gentle ballads, “All at Once You Love Her” (the musical’s hit song) and “The Next Time It Happens.” Fauna had two particularly striking songs, the title number jamboree and the amusingly solemn turn-of-the-century-styled ballad that extolled her place of business as “The Happiest House on the Block.” Another pleasant ballad was “Will You Marry Me?,” a trunk number left over from South Pacific.\n\nMany of the critics felt Rodgers and Hammerstein weren’t entirely comfortable with the marginalized characters of Steinbeck’s Cannery Row, and much was made of their white-washing of Suzy from a prostitute to a kind of vagrant waif who lives in a huge abandoned steel boiler, which was her personal pipe dream. John Chapman in the Daily News suggested Rodgers and Hammerstein were “too gentlemanly” to deal with the “sleazy and raffish” vagrants and prostitutes of Cannery Row, and Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times noted that love as depicted in Pipe Dream fell back on the traditions of the musical stage and thus Rodgers’s “enchanting music” kept love “on a high romantic plane.”\n\nWalter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune felt the musical was too obsessed with the “philosophy” of the “life is real, life is earnest” school, but noted Rodgers’s “sometimes wonderfully melodic” score took over and offered “genuine gaiety”; but while the evening promised a “party,” someone forgot “to bring along that gallon jug of good red wine.”\n\nRichard Watts in the New York Post said Rodgers and Hammerstein were “hardly” at their peak in Pipe Dream, and he was “disappointed” in the musical’s aimlessness and lack of excitement; of the cast, Judy Tyler deserved the “highest credit” (Chapman said she was “a real find for the musical theatre”) but Helen Traubel was “less than comfortable” as the madam. William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun noted the production was “casual” and “leisurely,” and the score’s “homely swaying beauty” was the kind of music “you might hope Stephen Foster would write in the modern idiom.” Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror said the musical was “no masterpiece” but “just a pretty good musical” with a “rather pedestrian” score.\n\nJohn McClain in the New York Journal-American liked the “good” score, but said the book wasn’t “engrossing” and thus he never had the “slightest interest” in the characters and the story. Further, he seemed unimpressed with the cast and thought the second-act masquerade ball was “disappointing.” The evening was a “far cry” from South Pacific, and he concluded that Rodgers and Hammerstein “must be human, after all.”\n\nDropped during preproduction were the songs “Nobody’s Fool,” “Cannery Row,” and “A Man of Some Intelligence.” It appears “Sitting on the Porch in the Moonlight,” which had been cut from Allegro, was at one point considered for Pipe Dream.\n\nThe original cast album was released by RCA Victor (LP # LOC-1023) and issued on CD by RCA/BMG (# 09026-61481-2). The script was published in hardback in 1956 by Viking Press, and the lyrics are included in The Collected Lyrics of Oscar Hammerstein II.\n\nA concert revival of Pipe Dream was produced by Encores! on March 28, 2012, for seven performances; the cast included Will Chase (Doc), Leslie Uggams (Fauna), Laura Osnes (Suzy), and Tom Wopat (Mac). The concert was recorded by Ghostlight (CD # B-4463).\n\nAn element of underlying sadness pervaded the overall score and story of Pipe Dream. Its short Broadway run was a major disappointment, and within a year of its closing, tragedy struck and its two young leads were dead. William Johnson died of a heart attack on March 6, 1957, at the age of forty-one, and on June 3, 1957, twenty-four-year-old Judy Tyler and her husband were killed in an automobile accident during their honeymoon.\n\nJohnson had the distinction of introducing on Broadway songs by Vernon Duke, Cole Porter, Alan Jay Lerner and Frederick Loewe, and Rodgers and Hammerstein. In Duke’s Banjo Eyes (1941), he introduced the jaunty “Not a Care in the World”; in Porter’s Something for the Boys (1943) he and Ethel Merman introduced “Hey, Good Lookin’”; and in Lerner and Loewe’s The Day Before Spring he sang “God’s Green World” and “You Haven’t Changed at All.” He also starred opposite Dolores Gray in the original 1947 Lon",
