    id: "the-vamp",
    title: "The Vamp",
    year: 1955,
    era: "golden-age",
    type: "musical",
    openingDate: "1955-11-10",
    closingDate: "1955-12-31",
    theatre: "Winter Garden Theatre",
    composer: "James Mundy (incidental music by Jack Pfeiffer)",
    lyricist: "John LaTouche",
    bookWriter: "John LaTouche and Sam Locke",
    director: "“Production” directed by David Alexander and “entire production” supervised by Robert Alton",
    choreographer: "Robert Alton",
    producer: "Oscar Lerman, Martin Cohen, and Alexander Carson (Manuel D. Herbert, Associate Producer)",
    songs: ["The Spiel","The Flickers","Keep Your Nose to the Grindstone","That’s Where a Man Fits In","I’ve Always Loved You","You’re Colossal","Fan Club Chant","Have You Met Delilah?","Yeemy Yeemy","The Vamps","Delilah’s Dilemma","Four Little Misfits","Samson and Delilah","Why Does It Have to Be You?","Ragtime Romeo","I’m Everybody’s Baby","The Impossible She"],
    performances: 60,
    synopsis: "There were a number of memorable songs and situations. Channing’s first number (“Keep Your Nose to the Grindstone”) was a hilarious rendering in song and pantomime of pig-tailed farm girl Flora’s typical day of feeding chickens, mowing hay, and fetching the well water. William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun praised her “mock clumsiness and innocent startlement,” and Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times said her “fabulous” performance in this sequence indicated that a “robust, knockabout show” would follow. Later, an amusing scene depicted two silent films being simultaneously shot by the same director and the same cast. And Channing stopped the show with the eleven o’clock number “I’m Everybody’s Baby,” a Jekyll-and-Hyde affair in which she depicted both her real self and her movie persona. There was another show-stopper with Bibi Osterwald’s “Ragtime Romeo,” which most critics praised as the score’s best number.\n\nAtkinson noted Channing was an “animated cartoon” whose accent was “like a bad dream of the Middle West,” and Walter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune said the “glorious zany” could drop her voice into the basement of the Winter Garden Theatre and say the word “human” as it “obviously” should be pronounced, “hew-min.”\n\nBut despite the often “droll” manner of the musical, Atkinson found it “shallow,” Hawkins said it was a “one-joke evening,” and Richard Watts in the New York Post felt the book wasn’t “funny or pointed” and sometimes overwhelmed the slender story with cumbersome details about the era’s filmmaking.\n\nThe critics were divided over Robert Alton and Raoul Pene du Bois’s contributions. Watts found Alton’s dances “invariably humorous, dynamic and exhilarating,” but Atkinson said they had an “empty, mechanical style.” As for du Bois’s décor, John McClain in the New York Journal-American said his concoctions were “extravagant and quite authentic” in their depictions of a barnyard in the Bronx, Grand Central Station, and a Hollywood studio; but Atkinson said the scenery wasn’t up to the designer’s usual standard.\n\nAnd while John LaTouche and James Mundy’s score was generally shrugged off by the seven New York critics, it’s notable that of the seventeen songs the reviewers singled out a total of eleven for praise. One suspects the score would have made a good cast album, which had actually been scheduled for recording by RCA Victor (LP # LOC-1022) and was cancelled due to the musical’s brief run.\n\nAfter the New York opening, two songs were dropped (“I’ve Always Loved You” and “The Impossible She”). During the tryout, the musical was titled Delilah, the role of Dolly (played by Helen Wood) was eliminated, and four songs were deleted: “Mr. Right,” “Back Home Where I Come From,” “You’ve Got to Give the Public What It Wants,” and “Little Miss Dracula.”\n\nDespite the lack of a cast album, a few delightful songs have surfaced. “Ragtime Romeo” can be heard in the collections Life’s a Funny Present (Rialto CD # SLRR-9306) and Unsung Musicals (Varese Sarabande CD # VSD-5462), and the collection Broadway Musicals of 1955 (Original Cast Records CD # OC-6224) offers three attractive numbers (“I’ve Always Loved You,” “Four Little Misfits,” and “Why Does It Have to Be You?”).\n\nSteve Reeves played the Muscle Man and Samson in the musical, and previously was one of the Wazir’s tough guards in Kismet. Type-casting and the movies soon called, and Reeves became a superstar in a series of loincloth epics.\n\nPerhaps The Vamp was done in by the Silent Movie Curse, a small subgenre of musicals that dealt with the early era of moviemaking and/or its celebrities and that inevitably failed at the box office. Besides The Vamp, others in this field are Goldilocks (1958; 161 performances) and Mack and Mabel (1974; 65 performances). Even Off-Off-Broadway’s Theda Bara and the Frontier Rabbi (1993), Dominic Argento’s opera The Dream of Valentino (1993), and Off-Broadway’s The IT Girl (2001; inspired by Clara Bow’s silent film It) seem to have disappeared after their initial productions. Further, two different musicals about Charlie Chaplin floundered; 1983’s Chaplin closed during its pre-Broadway tryout, and a second Chaplin opened on Broadway in 2012 and ran for only 135 performances. The 1966 Italian musical Ciao, Rudy (which starred Marcello Mastroianni as Valentino) and its 1972 revival were popular in Italy (and both productions enjoyed cast recordings), but the musical perhaps wisely never tested the Broadway waters.\n\nIn his review of The Vamp, Kerr noted that “move-making in New York in 1913” was “ready for exploitation,” and three years later he, his wife Jean Kerr, Jean Ford, and composer Leroy Anderson wrote Goldilocks, another tribute to making silent movies in the New York of 1913. Despite an amusing book and a delicious score, the show didn’t make it, but at least it left behind a rousing cast album.",
