    songs: ["It’s a Perfect Relationship","Hello, Hello There!","Is It a Crime?","I Met a Girl","Long Before I Knew You","Just in Time","Drop That Name","The Party’s Over","I’m Going Back","Bells Are Ringing","On My Own","Independent","You’ve Got to Do It","It’s a Simple Little System","Hello, Hello, There!","Mu-Cha-Cha","Salzburg","The Midas Touch","I’m Goin’ Back","I’m Goin’ Back,"],
    performances: 924,
    synopsis: "Ever since appearing with Judy Holliday in a nightclub revue, Betty Comden and Adolph Green had wanted to write a musical for her. The story they eventually hit upon was one in which Miss Holliday played Ella Peterson, a chatty telephone operator at the Susanswerphone service (run by Jean Stapleton) who gets so involved with one client, playwright Jeff Moss (Sydney Chaplin), that — without revealing her identity — she arranges to meet him and help him overcome his writer’s block. They also sing and dance in the subway, entertain fellow New Yorkers in Central Park, and fall in love. With Miss Holliday’s winning performance and a score containing three enduring songs (“Long Before I Knew You,” “Just in Time,” and “The Party’s Over”), Bells Are Ringing had the longest run of the eight musicals written together by Styne, Comden and Green. Miss Holliday repeated her role in the 1960 movie version, which also starred Dean Martin.\n\nCandide. Max Adrian, Louis Edmonds, Barbara Cook, and Robert Rounseville. (Friedman-Abeles)",
