    performances: 21,
    funFact: "Although he died during the early stages of the subsequent stage production, Hilton shared book credit with Jerome Lawrence and Robert E.",
    synopsis: "During the chaotic tryout of Shangri-La, Lew Ayres was replaced by Dennis King, and Susan Cabot by Shirley Yamaguchi; director Marshall Jamison was succeeded by Albert Marre; nine songs were deleted (“In the Hollow of His Hand,” “What Do You Do,” “Men Are Only Little Boys Grown Tall,” “Moderation,” “Every Night,” “No Night to Fear,” “I Never Had the Time,” “Learn the Old Soft Shoe,” and “Listen to the Sound of My Love”); and the script was almost completely rewritten. And if all this wasn’t enough, John McClain in the New York Journal-American reported that the day before the New York opening a “scenic mountain” that weighed a ton fell over backstage.\n\nBut all the doctoring on the musical was for naught and it lasted less than three weeks. The headline for Robert Coleman’s review in the Daily Mirror proclaimed that “‘Shangri-La’ Has Limited Horizon,” and he said the score wasn’t memorable and the story was treated “cerebrally rather than emotionally.” But he had the highest praise for Peter Larkin’s “unbelievably stunning and ingenious sets” (which included cloudy Plexiglas-like formations lit from within); John Chapman in the Daily News noted that Hilton’s original novel was “imaginative” but the musical had gone to “extraordinary lengths to de-imagine it” and so despite its “visual splendors” it left him ”as cold as a penguin’s toes”; and Frances Herridge in the New York Post said the musical became a “beautifully dressed bore” when it resorted to dances and big production numbers; but Alice Ghostley was a “delight” and her “I’m Just a Little Bit Confused” was the musical’s funniest song (otherwise, Harry Warren’s score was “neither distinguished nor infectious”).\n\nBut William Hawkins in the New York World-Telegram and Sun and John McClain were pleased with the new musical. Hawkins said it was “a most extraordinarily agreeable evening” as well as a “curious and unusual one,” and Shirley Yamaguchi was “the most exquisite figure to arrive on Broadway in years.” McClain liked the musical’s “many brilliant and bounteous moments,” and he praised Larkin’s “colossally brilliant” sets and Irene Sharaff’s “dazzling and imaginative” costumes. But he noted that some of the book scenes were “plain dreary,” and the High Lama’s discussion about the background and philosophy of Shangri-La was given an “exhaustive airing” that should have been severely edited.\n\nThe two most influential critics gave the musical a thumbs-down. Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times said that except for Shirley Yamaguchi the musical was “swamped in production and routines,” but he praised the “Himalayan magnificence” of Larkin’s “spectacular” scenery. Walter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune said the musical had neglected to provide any “fun,” and so a clichéd welcome dance by the natives for the plane crash survivors was “prolonged” and the visitors had to stand there and watch with feigned interest. He too pounced on the scene with the High Lama, noting that as the scene progressed the orchestra played “slumbrously on,” and the story was developed with “lassitude, Shangri-lassitude, I guess.” He also mentioned that a character proclaimed that upon entering Shangri-La he felt the world “had stopped turning on its axis.” Kerr noted, “As the evening wore on, so did I.”\n\nA television adaptation was produced on NBC’s Hallmark Hall of Fame on October 24, 1960, with Richard Basehart (Conway), Marisa Pavan (Lo-Tsen), Helen Gallagher (Rita), Gene Nelson (Robert), Claude Rains (High Lama), and, from the original Broadway production, Alice Ghostley who reprised her role of Miss Brinklow and sang two of her numbers from the stage version, “I’m Just a Little Bit Confused” and “In the Hollow of His Hand” (the latter had been dropped during the tryout). Besides “In the Hollow of His Hand” and “Men Are Only Little Boys Grown Tall” (which had also been dropped during the tryout) and the new song “A Man in the Dark,” eight songs were retained from the Broadway production: “Om Mani Padme Hum,” “Lost Horizon,” “Shangri-La,” “I’m Just a Little Bit Confused,” “The World Outside,” “Walk Sweet,” “Love Is What I Never Knew,” and “Second Time in Love.” George Schaefer directed the adaptation, and Jay Blackton conducted. The television soundtrack was issued by The Sound of Broadway (LP # 300) and was paired with the 1960 television adaptation of Shinbone Alley.\n\nThe collection Lost Broadway and More (Original Cast Records CD [unnumbered]) includes “Shangri-La”; Judy Kaye’s Where, Oh Where: Rare Songs of the American Theatre (Premier CD # PRCD-1001) includes “Lost Horizon”; and Ballet on Broadway (Painted Smiles CD # PSCD-149) offers the “Father Perrault Ballet” with narration by Wyatt Cooper (the music is credited to Warren, not Pitot).\n\nIn 1973, Columbia released a new musical version of Hilton’s novel, which Clive Hirschhorn in The Hollywood Musical said was “probably the worst musical of the decade” (Leonard Maltin’s Movie Guide said “’Lost’ is right”). Produce",
