    closingDate: "1957-05-25",
    theatre: "Broadway Theatre",
    composer: "George Kleinsinger",
    lyricist: "Joe Darion",
    bookWriter: "Joe Darion and Mel Brooks",
    director: "Production supervised by Sawyer Falk",
    choreographer: "Rod Alexander (“additional” choreography by Arthur Mitchell)",
    producer: "Peter Lawrence",
    songs: ["What Do We Care?","Toujours gai","Queer Little Insect","Big Bill","True Romance","The Lightning Bug Song","I Gotta Be","Dog and Cat Ballet","Flotsam and Jetsam","Come to Mee-ow","Suicide Song","Shinbone Alley","The Moth Song","A Woman Wouldn’t Be a Woman","The Lullaby","What the Hell","Pretty Kitty","Way Down Blues","The Lady Bug Song","Vacant Lot Ballet","Be a Pussycat","Quiet Street","Toujours Gai"],
    performances: 49,
    funFact: "While Shinbone Alley's plot was thin, it had abundant charm and daring, and Rod Alexander's choreography was among the best of its time.",
    synopsis: "Before the Broadway opening, director Norman Lloyd left the production and thus no director was listed in the program, which noted the production was “supervised” by Sawyer Falk (John McClain in the New York Journal-American said Shinbone Alley was “the first show in recent memory which apparently staged itself”). During the run, the program didn’t always list Rod Alexander as the musical’s choreographer; for example, the program for the week of April 29 didn’t list any dance credits; the one for May 6 credited Arthur Mitchell as Alexander’s assistant but otherwise didn’t mention Alexander; and the one for May 20 credited Mitchell for “additional” choreography without any mention of Alexander. During the run, the second act was completely restructured with a major reordering of some numbers (“Vacant Lot Ballet” was moved from the eighth to the second scene); the deletion of others (“What the Hell,” “Way Down Blues,” and “Quiet Street”); and the addition of “Mehitabel’s a House Cat” (for Bracken, George S. Irving, and the ensemble).\n\nThe musical had no real plot, and was in essence a revue-styled evening that focused on the eccentricities of Shinbone Alley’s denizens, including the cat Mehitabel, who doesn’t care to be domesticated; the cockroach Archy, who is forever contemplating suicide; the lightning bug Broadway (Ross Martin), so named because he can blink on and off like one of Broadway’s neon signs; tom-cat bully Big Bill (George S. Irving); and artistic cat Tyrone T. Tattersal (Erik Rhodes).\n\nBrooks Atkinson in the New York Times praised George Kleinsinger’s score of “humor, drollery, street tunes and juke-box pandemonium,” and singled out Kitt and Bracken’s “exuberantly” sung “Flotsam and Jetsam,” which was “excellent.” He also liked the “ferocious scramble” of the “Cat and Dog Ballet” and the “beautifully designed’ “Vacant Lot Ballet.” But unfortunately the score and the performers were involved in “episodes,” and there was nothing in the way of a coherent plot (and he noted what plot there was “disintegrates” in the second act). Walter Kerr in the New York Herald-Tribune regretted that the “unlinked vignettes” offered a “collection” of songs but no real narrative. But he praised the “rollicking” soft-shoe “Flotsam and Jetsam” and Kitt’s “thoroughly fetching impudence.” Richard Watts in the New York Post said the “singularly ineffectual” book got “monotonous” when it didn’t altogether “disappear,” and the occasional wisps of plot faded into “nothingness.” He also noted that “chaos” took over in the second act, and mentioned that the “Vacant Lot Ballet” set “new records for not being integrated into the narrative.”\n\nTom Donnelly in the New York World-Telegram and Sun felt the residents of Shinbone Alley were “involved in a rather cluttered revue,” but he praised the “glittering” Kitt and the “wistful and appealing” Bracken. He noted the two teamed up “expertly” in “Flotsam and Jetsam,” which was the evening’s “show-stopper.” John Chapman in the Daily News liked the “captivating” and “whimsical” musical, and said Kleinsinger’s music was “original” and “witty” and “bubbles over with the happiest score in town.” It was “wonderful stuff” filled with the “gusto” of the back-alley, and he singled out “The Lullaby,” in which the female cats croon over a basketful of newborn kittens while in counterpoint their mother, Kitt, curses them.\n\nMcClain felt the “floundering” book and the “curiously lacklustre score” added up to a “near miss” for Shinbone Alley. But he singled out nine songs, and noted that Kitt and Bracken’s “Flotsam and Jetsam” was “sheer artistry” which “held up the proceedings for endless encores.”\n\nThe Columbia concept album Archy and Mehitabel (LP # OL-4963; issued on CD by DRG, # 19064) was subtitled “A Back-Alley Opera,” and besides Channing and Bracken the recording included David Wayne as a narrator. Years later, concept albums (such as the ones for Jesus Christ Superstar and Evita) would be more common as forerunners of eventually staged productions, but in the 1950s this was a new phenomenon. Following Archy and Mehitabel, the next concept album was Clara (1959), which evolved into the 1960 Broadway musical Beg, Borrow or Steal.\n\nOnce Shinbone Alley closed, one might have assumed it was gone forever. But as Archy and Mehitabel it resurfaced on television’s Play of the Week on March 16, 1960; produced by David Susskind, it starred Eddie Bracken, Tammy Grimes (Mehitabel), Michael Kermoyan (Big Bill), Sondra Lee, and Jules Munshin. A later LP release by The Sound of Broadway (# 300) included five songs from the telecast (“Flotsam and Jetsam,” “Come to Mee-ow,” “Romeo and Juliet,” “Pretty Kitty,” and “The Lady Bug Song” along with an orchestral prelude and a finale; the album also included two songs performed by Eartha Kitt, “Toujours Gai” and “A Woman Wouldn’t Be a Woman”). Included on the recording were songs from the 1960 television version of Shangri-La.\n\nIn 1971, a cartoon film version",
