    id: "goldilocks",
    title: "Goldilocks",
    year: 1958,
    era: "golden-age",
    type: "musical",
    openingDate: "1958-10-11",
    closingDate: "1959-02-28",
    theatre: "Lunt-Fontanne Theatre",
    composer: "Leroy Anderson",
    lyricist: "Joan Ford, Walter Kerr, and Jean Kerr",
    bookWriter: "Walter Kerr and Jean Kerr",
    director: "Walter Kerr",
    choreographer: "Agnes de Mille",
    producer: "The Producers Theatre (A Robert Whitehead Production)",
    songs: ["Lazy Moon","Give the Little Lady","Save a Kiss","No One’ll Ever Love You","Who’s Been Sitting in My Chair?","Dance","There Never Was a Woman","The Pussy Foot","Huckleberry Island Ballet","Pirate Orgy","Pirate Dance","Lady in Waiting","The Beast in You","Shall I Take My Heart and Go?","Bad Companions","I Can’t Be in Love","I Never Know When","The Town House Maxixe","Two Years in the Making","Heart of Stone","Pyramid Dance"],
    performances: 161,
    funFact: "The part of Max changed hands twice: Ben Gazzara was originally signed, then asked to be released; he was replaced by Barry Sullivan, who had been originally sought and was now available.",
    synopsis: "Walter and Jean Kerr’s book was quite amiable, but just missed the final touch of wit and zaniness that one expected of them; but their lyrics (with co-lyricist Joan Ford) were always on target, and “No One’ll Ever Love You,” “There Never Was a Woman,” and “The Beast in You” were amusing songs that depicted the characters’ various comic annoyances with one another; “Two Years in the Making” was a delightful bit of tongue-in-cheek; and the unjustly ignored blues, the haunting “I Never Know When” was one of the best ballads of the era (but of the seven New York critics, only John McClain in the New York Journal-American singled it out).\n\nOne feels the musical needed more tweaking (and perhaps just one more stop on the tryout road for additional rewriting) in order to better clarify the relationship of Max and Maggie, and to satisfyingly resolve the storylines involving George and Lois. And that title needed to go. Many potential ticket buyers were probably turned off in the belief the musical was aimed at children (and while delightful in itself, the artwork logo for the window card and the cast album didn’t help in its depiction of a fanciful rendering of Stritch and a jolly dancing bear in what appears to be a mock minuet). And the title was loaded, because everyone knew the story of Goldilocks and the three bears and no doubt many in the audience assumed the musical was a sly update and thus tried to figure out how the moviemaking plot fit in with the famous story.\n\nAnd while the critics generally praised Agnes de Mille’s choreography (especially “The Town House Maxixe,” “The Pussy Foot,” and “Lady in Waiting”), perhaps six dance numbers (the other three were the Stritch-and-dancing bear sequence and the “Huckleberry Island Ballet” [after the opening, its title was changed to the “Pirate Orgy”] and “Pyramid Dance”) were a couple too many for an essentially comic musical.\n\nOn the other hand, since the musical was about moviemaking in the silent era, maybe it was predestined that Goldilocks would never join the winner’s circle. As noted in the entry for The Vamp, there seems to be a Silent-Movie Curse when it comes to musicals dealing with the subject (including Mack & Mabel) or with stars of that era (such as Chaplin and Valentino).\n\nRichard Watts in the New York Post proclaimed that drama critics and their wives were “notoriously more brilliant than most people,” and thus Goldilocks was a “disappointment” (and he wished there had been more witty dialogue of the kind written for Margaret Hamilton’s character). He noted that the dance accompanying “Lady in Waiting” (in which Pat Stanley conjures up images of the kind of men she wishes would pursue her) revealed a fresh and imaginative approach that the evening as a whole never quite achieved. McClain was also “disappointed,” and while the musical was sometimes “extremely funny” and often “melodious,” the book was “woefully slight” and “unresolved.” Frank Aston in the New York World-Telegram and Sun said the musical’s “parts surpassed the whole” and rarely developed a “personality of its own.” But he singled out the Egyptian take-off as “whoopingly funny,” and noted that visually the musical was “magnificent” with its ”ice-blues, yellows, grays and golds.”\n\nRobert Coleman in the Daily Mirror said Walter Kerr directed the “frolic” with “the speed of a hungry steed on the ways to oats in his stable” and the “thread of a story” was loaded with “hilarious wisecracks.” While the musical was no “gem,” there were “several high spots” to enjoy, including a “zany take-off” of a grandiose Egyptian epic filmed in a wintry corn field near the Hudson River where the extras shiver in their Egyptian togs as the movie-made ponds ice over, light snow begins to fall, and the only way to keep warm is to get near the steam-blowing Egyptian idol-statuary. He also noted that some of the lyrics had “the sting of a scorpion.” John Chapman in the Daily News said Goldilocks was a “funny” musical, and “they don’t hardly make them no more.”\n\nWith the exception of its score and production values, Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times found the new musical “unexciting.” The “uninteresting” book was without focus and thus the plot was “loose, vague and trifling.” But the dialogue was “sharp and deadly” and the music was “charming.”\n\nFor the New York Herald Tribune, Herbert Whittaker substituted for Walter Kerr, and said when spoofing early moviemaking the musical offered “a great deal of pleasure”; but the romantic plot was presented along more conventional lines, and at times he thought the story was more about Lois than the Max-Maggie-George triangle.\n\nEarly flyers advertised Ben Gazzara as the male lead, but he dropped out in preproduction; as the show neared its tryout, Barry Sullivan was brought in, but he too decamped; and so Don Ameche assumed the role about midway through the tryout. The tryout programs indicated the action took place in 1914, but for some reason the year was pushe",
