    funFact: "She was replaced by another popular singer, Polly Bergen, with Farley Granger cast as Darcy and Hermione Gingold as Mrs.",
    synopsis: "The plot closely followed Austen, and focused on both the relationship of the stubborn and independent Elizabeth Bennet (Polly Bergen) and the rich and arrogant Fitzwilliam Darcy (Farley Granger) and the attempts of her mother Mrs. Bennet (Hermione Gingold) to marry off Elizabeth and her four sisters. Some critics were unhappy that a few characters (such as Mr. Bennet) were mere walk-ons, but the exigencies of any adaptation, especially a musical one, necessitated a certain amount of trimming and deletions. As such, the script reads well and does its work efficiently and sometimes brilliantly. Moreover, while the lovely score was not in the class of My Fair Lady, it was nonetheless a richly melodic one that told the story, defined character, and created atmosphere.\n\nThe score included “Love Will Find Out the Way,” a gorgeous ballad for Elizabeth that in many ways served as the musical’s theme song. Played on a pianoforte, the number was ravishingly sung by Polly Bergen, who was also strikingly effective in her two character songs, “I’m Me” and “This Really Isn’t Me.” Darcy wasn’t served quite so well, and his big number “Gentlemen Don’t Fall Wildly in Love” seemed like a reject from My Fair Lady. But his two songs with Elizabeth, their sardonic “A Perfect Evening” and their jubilant “I Suddenly Find You (It) Agreeable,” were delightful. And his ballad (and its later reprise with Elizabeth) “The Heart Has Won the Game” was pure Austen set to music, as it resolved the couple’s pride and prejudice and brought them to a happy conclusion.\n\nElizabeth and Mrs. Bennet shared one of the evening’s highlights, the fetching “Let’s Fetch the Carriage,” and there were two delightful gossip numbers. The music of “Have You Heard the News?” was as prettily prancing as a spring pony as it enveloped the town with titters of speculation about Darcy’s arrival at Netherfield Hall, and “Wasn’t It a Simply Lovely Wedding?” (also known as “Wedding Gossip”) dissected a local wedding from the perspectives of gushing enthusiasm (from almost everyone) and sarcastic asides (from Mrs. Bennet). And “I Feel Sorry for the Girl” was an English garden-party frolic for Jane (Phyllis Newman) and her friends.\n\nThere was also evocative dance music throughout, including a polka, a mazurka, the assembly dance, a second-act excursion for three dancing couples (which followed “I Feel Sorry for the Girl”), and a late second-act dance for Wickham (James Mitchell) and his cronies. Richard Watts in the New York Post noted Jonathan Lucas’s “gay and imaginative choreography” used dance to forward the narrative, and Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times praised the “formal elegance” of the “Assembly Dance.”\n\nThe most controversial aspect of the evening was the casting of Hermione Gingold as Mrs. Bennet. She in some ways embodied the problem of adapting Austen for the musical stage. Should the adaptation be done straight, or should there be traditional musical-comedy flavoring? Gingold was always an acquired taste, and it’s clear the authors, director, and Gingold herself concluded that the essentially common and superficial nature of Mrs. Bennet should dominate her characterization. And so her music-hall approach to the role enchanted some and annoyed most. However, the critics noted the audience was delighted with her, and according to John McClain in the New York Journal-American, she “brought the proceedings to a full halt” with the march “As Long as There’s a Mother” and her soliloquy “A House in Town.”\n\nAs for the musical-comedy madness of “A House in Town,” for some listeners it’s the highpoint of the score and one of the best comedy songs of the era. Throughout the evening, Mrs. Bennet has attempted to marry off her daughters, and here in this one number it becomes clear their nuptials are for her and her alone because the marriages will boost her social position and financial standing (before going into the song, she proclaims, “When I’m rich—and I will be rich”). Alone on the stage in deep fantasy, this dominating mother’s reverie depicts her dreams of money, prestige, and a house in town (with all its accoutrements, including a different cook for every meal). Yes, two months before Gypsy opened, we have “Mrs. Bennet’s Turn,” in which the simmering frustrations of the character suddenly emerge full-boil into a music-hall routine that pulls out all the stops. And like Mama Rose, Mrs. Bennet talks back to the orchestra, which she admonishes by insisting that a “delicate fanfare” accompany her entrance to the grand soiree of her dreams.\n\nMcClain noted the musical was a “highly decorative, mostly amusing and tuneful extravaganza,” the choreography was “excellent” and “exceptional,” and the “sprightly and often haunting” score was deserving of “happy” accolades. He and other critics were especially taken with Peter Larkin’s décor and Alvin Colt’s costumes, and he singled out the “brilliant” opening curtain, which depicted a gigantic lady’s fan that then",
