    theatre: "54th Street Theatre",
    composer: "Gordon Duffy (additional music by Paul Nassau)",
    lyricist: "Harry M. Haldane (additional lyrics by Paul Nassau)",
    bookWriter: "Book “adaptation” by Max Hampton",
    director: "Allan A. Buckhantz",
    choreographer: "Lee Scott",
    producer: "B & M Productions",
    songs: ["It Isn’t Easy","Celebration!","Something Special","The Legend of Black-Eyed Susan Grey","Opportunity!","As Busy as Anyone Can Be","Heaven Protect Me!","I Feel Like a Brother to You!","Hoedown!","I Am What I Am!","The Beat of a Heart","Mean","When the Time Is Right","Pick-Me-Up!","I’m Stuck with Love","Talkin’ about You","Y’ Can’t Win","Opportunity","The Embassy Waltz!,","On the Street Where You Live!,","Ascot Gavotte!"],
    performances: 5,
    funFact: "Happy Town had closed after a week's tryout in Boston for a complete rewrite, but it unwisely came in to town as the first musical of the 1959-60 season.",
    synopsis: "The plot of Happy Town was so unclear a few critics said they weren’t quite sure of its details. In the main, Back-A-Heap is the only town in Texas without a millionaire, and so four nefarious multimillionaire brothers dispatch their innocent young brother Craig (Biff McGuire) to the town to encourage the citizens to sell their property to his brothers’ syndicate. In this way, everyone in town will be rich. But unknown to Craig is that great oil reserves lie beneath the town, and what the brothers will pay to the townsfolk is a pittance compared to the oil profits they’ll reap once they own the town. The plot also included a romance between Craig and the local preacher’s daughter Molly (Lee Venora); the machinations of the wicked Janice (Cindy Robbins) who is in cahoots with the brothers; and local stud Clint Yoder (Tom Williams) who is on the make for each and every young female in the vicinity.\n\nActually, one critic compared Happy Town to My Fair Lady. (But not in a good way.) Brooks Atkinson in the New York Times noted the cast of the new musical worked as hard as if they’d been in the Lerner and Loewe masterpiece, but their work was to no avail. “Even if the details of the plot could be understood,” the musical would still have been “lifeless,” “routine,” and “profoundly uninteresting.”\n\nAnd two of the critics compared Happy Town to Portofino. (But in a good way.) They agreed Happy Town wasn’t quite as bad. Richard Watts in the New York Post said the best thing he could say about the show was that it was “terrible” and “not quite another Portofino, but fairly close,” and John McClain in the New York Journal-American noted it wasn’t a “spectacular ‘bomb’ in the classic tradition of Portofino, which burst upon an incredulous populace” at the same theatre (the playhouse was known as the Adelphi when Portofino opened, and as the 54th Street Theatre when Happy Town premiered). But McClain mentioned the new musical was “almost as boring” as Portofino “in its sheer mediocrity.”\n\nWatts said the musical was a “resounding musical comedy disaster,” and McClain mentioned the only reason he sat through the second act of the “expensive disaster” was because of a sudden downpour outside. Frank Aston in the New York World-Telegram and Sun said the “befuddled” musical was “virtually all bad,” and if you thought the names of the musical’s creators seemed “dull” then “you should have been there for the performance.” He too felt the plot was confusing, and noted its details were “not clear to this benumbed onlooker.” Robert Coleman in the Daily Mirror said the “musical misdemeanor” was a “smash-up instead of a smash hit,” and wrongly predicted that choreographer Lee Scott’s “spirited” dances would “give him another shot at the big-time.” John Chapman in the Daily News said the musical was “quite a serious accident” and offered his sympathy to the “injured.” But he liked Tom Williams’s randy ranch hand, and noted that Scott’s choreography was “energetic, acrobatic and unflaggingly lively.”\n\nWalter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune said no one struck theatrical oil in Happy Town. He mentioned that McGuire and Verona sang duets (he ruefully noted there were “quite a few, quite a few”), there were perhaps four “discreet” jokes during the entire evening (one from a ranch hand who spends a lot of time at rodeos and is thus “rodeo-active”), and that for a musical reportedly backed by actual Texas millionaires the show was surprisingly “economy-minded” and thus the backdrops and cardboard mountains were “wrinkled” and the whole “wobbly caboodle” offered “some of the least attractive scenery to visit Broadway in many months.” Even a supermarket scene was not very “super.”\n\nAs mentioned, during its tryout the musical temporarily closed for rewrites, none of which did any good; and by the time of the New York opening there was no official book writer credited in the program except for the notation that Max Hampton had “adapted” the book. During the tryout, Henry Hull left the musical and was succeeded by Edwin Steffe.\n\nThe 1959–1960 season was not a kind one for the genial and talented Biff McGuire. He had leading roles in both Happy Town and Beg, Borrow or Steal, both of which closed after five performances apiece.\n\nAnd consider the plight of poor Cindy Robbins. Her program biography noted that with the release of her first movie This Earth Is Mine she was “immediately hailed as being Hollywood’s newest and most exciting personality.” Her studio “naturally started making all sorts of fabulous plans” for her, but when Happy Town came along “she packed her bags, locked up her apartment, and said goodbye to Hollywood.” And before long she was also saying goodbye to Broadway.",
