    funFact: "For that show and for the first time in his career, Blitzstein let someone else write the book.",
    synopsis: "The family is comprised of the irresponsible Boyle (the paycock, played by Melvyn Douglas), his tormented son, Johnny (Tommy Rall), who has secretly aided the despised British army, his hopeful daughter, Mary (Monte Amundsen), and his suffering wife, Juno (Shirley Booth), who holds the family together without any help from the vain and useless Boyle. Despite his airs of grandeur, the paycock is little more than an eternally unemployed bounder who spends whatever money he has on drinks at the local pub where he hangs out with the superficial and conniving Joxer (Jack MacGowran). Nothing is easy in Juno’s life, and when it appears the family will inherit a fortune, she can for the first time in her life look to the future with hope. Boyle holds a lavish party to celebrate the forthcoming riches, but soon the dream of a comfortable future is dashed when the inheritance proves to be a misunderstanding.\n\nJuno’s disappointment over the inheritance is nothing compared to the tragedies awaiting her. Johnny is executed by the Irish rebels when they discover he’s a traitor, and Mary becomes pregnant, deserted by both the baby’s father, Bentham (Earl Hammond), and by her longtime suitor, Jerry (Loren Driscoll), who will have nothing to do with her once he realizes she’s been unfaithful.\n\nWith her son dead, Mary pregnant, and Boyle completely useless, Juno takes stock of her life and with Mary leaves Dublin to make a new beginning in another town. No musical ever had such a devastatingly bleak ending. As the curtain fell, Boyle and Joxer are obliviously drunk as they sing “Daarlin’ Man” while Juno and Mary leave their home for the last time, two forlorn figures with valises in hand. The final curtain was perhaps the most bitter and ironic ever depicted on the musical stage, and was a complete departure from the era’s conventions of a happy ending or even a semi-happy ending, for there was no convincing reason to believe Juno and Mary will find much in the way of future happiness.\n\nThe tragic story was set to Blitzstein’s glorious score, a grand music-box of thirty individual musical numbers that propelled the narrative, explored character, and provided a rich atmosphere to the Irish setting. The first act began with the stirring chorus of “We’re Alive,” a defiant warning from the Dubliners to the British; the pulsating and majestic song is one of the most forceful opening numbers ever heard on the Broadway stage. And there were lush ballads for Mary (“I Wish It So,” “My True Heart,” and “For Love”); a haunting and breathtakingly sung “One Kind Word” for Jerry; incisive character songs for Juno (“Song of the Ma” and “Where?”) and Boyle (“Where Is the Stars?”); a rousing barroom folderol for Boyle and his cronies (“Daarlin’ Man”); a simpering comic quartet for the neighborhood gossips in all their shabby lace-curtain glory (“You Poor Thing”); an extended piece for the Boyles and the ensemble that anticipates the Boyles’ newfound fortune (“On a Day Like This”); and an array of songs in the old Irish style, the tearjerker “It’s Not Irish” (“to deny your dear old mother”), the patriotic “We Can Be Proud” (“that we’re from Ireland”), and a giddy, swirling salute to Dublin’s scenic attractions in the sweeping and swaying “The Liffey Waltz” with its purposely exaggerated rhymes.\n\nThe songs are so rich that each one seems to top the other in musical and lyrical splendor. And then Blitzstein all but topped himself with “Bird upon the Tree,” the score’s finest achievement and arguably the best theatre song of the era. At the party, Juno and Mary sing a “madrigally” song about a bird whose leg is caught in its nest. A fierce storm arises, and the trapped bird is unable to break free and find shelter; but suddenly the ravages of the storm tear apart the nest, dislodge the bird’s leg, and allow the bird to fly away to safety. Ironically, it’s the storm that frees the bird upon the tree. And so it is with Juno and Mary, as the song foreshadows how their political and personal storms will finally provide them the impetus to break free of Boyle and their Dublin prison.\n\nMany critics missed the mark with Juno. Although Candide and House of Flowers were box-office failures, they had advocates who recognized their intrinsic merits. But Juno lacked a fervent disciple to herald its genius. Joseph Stein’s powerful adaptation was underrated, and many critics overlooked the epic scope of Blitzstein’s richly melodic score. As such, the musical closed after two weeks.\n\nBrooks Atkinson in the New York Times noted that the “bold” “We’re Alive” offered an “overwhelming dance, song and dramatic incident” to open the musical, praised the “Irish and melodic” songs, and said Agnes de Mille’s “festive ballets admirably capture the decorum of Irish folk dancing.” But he felt the musical lacked “the drive, the scorn and the fury” of O’Casey’s original drama. Although Walter Kerr in the New York Herald Tribune singled out a few musical sequences (“The Liff",
