    performances: 286,
    synopsis: "A gentle, nostalgic look at a French-Canadian family, The Happy Time was adapted from the novel by Robert Fontaine and the play by Samuel Taylor. The story is primarily concerned with the coming of age of Bibi Bonnard (Mike Rupert) and his desire to see the world with his Uncle Jacques (Robert Goulet), a footloose magazine photographer who has returned to his family for a brief visit. But Grandpère Bonnard (David Wayne) who manages — with Jacques’ help — to convince Bibi to remain at home. The use of blow-up photographs to establish the mood for the various scenes was one of director Gower Champion’s most effective touches. The Happy Time bore a certain resemblance to 110 in the Shade, a previous musical by N. Richard Nash that had also been presented by David Merrick. That one also offered a smooth-talking visitor to a small town who excites the people’s imagination, and leaves them with renewed appreciation of their own values.",
