    wonBestMusical: true,
    performances: 10000,
    funFact: "Julie Taymor was the first woman to win the Tony for Best Direction of a Musical. The show has grossed over $1 billion on Broadway alone.",
    synopsis: "Disney’s first Broadway production, Beauty and the Beast, faithfully recreated a film into a three-dimensional theater piece. The Lion King roared onto the stage with such imaginative use of masks, puppetry, modern dance, music, and color, from the opening African chant song — which segues into “Circle of Life,” with a parade of animals in both aisles of the theater — to the reprise of “Circle of Life” finale, that Julie Taymor’s The Lion King is truly theatrical.\n\nThe slightly expanded story follows the screenplay. Mufasa (Samuel E. Wright) and his wife Sarabi (Gina Breedlove) present their new heir to the people. Scar (John Vickery), Mufasa’s evil brother, covets the throne for himself. After Mufasa is murdered, Scar banishes young Simba (Scott Irby-Ranniar). Eventually, after battling his uncle and his own personal fears, the grown-up Simba (Jason Raize) and Nala (Heather Headley) return to take over the pride. During the run, Mary Randle replaced Heather Headley, David “Dakota” Sanchez replaced Scott Irby-Ranniar, and Imani Parks replaced Kajuama Shuford.",
