    songs: ["It Sucks to Be Me","The Internet Is for Porn","s a Little Bit Racist\", ",", \"There","The Avenue Q Theme","What Do You Do with a B.A. in English?","If You Were Gay","Purpose","Everyone’s a Little Bit Racist","Mix Tape","I’m Not Wearing Underwear Today","Special","You Can Be as Loud as the Hell You Want (When You’re Makin’ Love)","Fantasies Come True","My Girlfriend, Who Lives in Canada","There’s a Fine, Fine Line","There Is Life Outside Your Apartment","The More You Ruv Someone","Schadenfreude","I Wish I Could Go Back to College","The Money Song","School for Monsters"],
    tonyWins: 3,
    tonyNominations: 6,
    wonBestMusical: true,
    performances: 2534,
    description: "Sesame Street for grown-ups. Puppets and humans share a low-rent New York neighborhood, navigating post-college disappointment with raunchy humor and surprising heart.",
    funFact: "The creators pitched it as \"Sesame Street with adult themes.\" Sesame Workshop was not amused but didn\\'t sue, reportedly because the parody was too obvious to confuse.",
    synopsis: "Avenue Q opened in 2002 at Off-Broadway’s Vineyard Theatre, quickly sold out, and then moved to Broadway, overcoming doubts as to whether this subversive “puppet show” was “too small” for Broadway.\n\nThe show is set in an a very far-off NYC borough that is the only place its disaffected, poorly employed denizens can afford to live because Manhattan is so forbiddingly expensive. The East Village goes up to Avenue D, and so the fictional Avenue Q is a lengthy extension. We meet a recent college graduate and his neighbors that include a kindergarten teacher, child star Gary Coleman who is now a building superintendent, an unemployed comedian and his uncredentialed therapist wife, and a male couple who may be gay. Together they commiserate and share their lives and problems.\n\nBesides the show’s comic and poignant score, its big appeal was designer and original cast member Rick Lyon’s awesome puppets. These are held by actors in plain sight, but the other characters react only to the puppets. Lyon worked on the classic PBS children’s series Sesame Street, and his creations have a jarring similarity, but here themes of racism, homosexuality, and pornography are addressed.\n\nAvenue Q repeated its previous success on Broadway and even managed to win the Tony Award for Best Musical. It has also been produced in London and Las Vegas.",
