    songs: ["Two Worlds","You’ll Be in My Heart","Jungle Funk","Who Better Than Me?","No Other Way","I Need to Know","Son of Man","Sure As Sun Turns to Moon","Waiting for This Moment","Trashin’ the Camp","Like No Man I’ve Ever Seen","Strangers Like Me","For the First Time","Everything That I Am"],
    performances: 486,
    synopsis: "With the triumph of Beauty and the Beast and The Lion King, Disney Theatrical Productions attempted a third success on Broadway with a stage adaptation of Disney’s 1999 animated film Tarzan. The bloated production was described in the New York Times as “a giant writhing green blob with music” and “a super deluxe daycare center.” Although Tarzan played for a year on Broadway, its success didn’t come close to matching those of its vaunted predecessors and closed after a year of poor reviews and limpid ticket sales.\n\nLike those of The Lion King, the songs, written by pop star Phil Collins, had an exotic African flavor and included the hit “You’ll Be in My Heart.” Collins augmented the five songs he penned for the film with nine more. The plot of the musical closely matched the film (both drawn from the original story by Edgar Rice Burroughs), with former American Idol contestant Josh Strickland making his stage debut as the free-swinging king of the jungle. This wasn’t the first time the loin-clothed yodeler had hit Broadway. A stage play, Tarzan of the Apes, starring Ronald Adair, swung into the Broadhurst Theater in 1921, but was also a failure.\n\nMusic: Mel Marvin Lyrics: Timothy Mason Book: Timothy Mason Producers: Running Subway, EMI Music Publishing, Michael Speyer, Bernie Abrams, Allen Spivak, Janet Pailet, Spark Productions, Maximum Entertainment, and Jonathan Reinis; presented by Target Stores Director: Matt August Choreographer: John DeLuca Cast: Patrick Page, John Cullum, Rusty Ross, Kaitlin Hopkins, Michael McCormick, Jan Neuberger, Price Waldman, Nicole Bocchi, Caroline London Songs: “Who Likes Christmas?”; “I Hate Christmas Eve”; “Whatchama Who”; “Welcome, Christmas” (music: Albert Hague; lyric: Dr. Seuss); “Once in a Year”; “One of a Kind”; “Now’s the Time”; “You’re a Mean One, Mr. Grinch” (music: Albert Hague; lyric: Dr. Seuss) New York run: Hilton Theatre, November 8, 2006; 107 p.; St. James Theatre, November 9, 2007; 96 p.\n\nWith the blessings of the estate of the late children’s author Theodore Geisel (a.k.a. “Dr. Seuss”), a musical based on Geisel’s book How the Grinch Stole Christmas was first staged in Minneapolis in 1994. The book had previously been dramatized as a 30-minute animated television special, narrated by Boris Karloff and featuring songs composed by Albert Hague with lyrics provided by Dr. Seuss himself. Two of the songs were included in the Broadway version.\n\nGrinch proved extremely popular and was brought back for seasonal revivals, with an annual production running in San Diego beginning in 1998. In 2006, it was produced for Broadway by Maximum Entertainment producer Avram C. Freedberg. With 12 performances a week, the most of any Broadway show up to that time, Grinch soon topped Wicked’s streak of 100 consecutive weeks as the top-grossing weekly musical.\n\nOne year later, the show was brought back for a return engagement, but striking stagehands halted production on its second day. Nearly two weeks later, with Bro",
