    director: "Thomas Kail",
    choreographer: "Andy Blankenbuehler",
    producer: "Kevin McCollum, Jeffrey Seller, Jill Furman, Sander Jacobs, Robyn Goodman, Walt Grossman, Peter Fine, Sonny Everett, Mike Skipper",
    notableCast: ["Lin-Manuel Miranda","Karen Olivo","Olga Merediz","Christopher Jackson","Andréa Burns","Janet Dacal","Robin De Jesús","Carlos Gomez","Mandy Gonzalez","Priscilla Lopez"],
    songs: ["In the Heights","96,000","Breathe","Paciencia y Fe","Carnaval del Barrio","Everything I Know","Benny’s Dispatch","It Won’t Be Long Now","Inutil","No Me Diga","Paciencia y Fe (Patience and Faith)","When You’re Home","Piragua","Siempre (Always)","The Club/ Fireworks","Sunrise","Hundreds of Stories","Enough","Atención","Alabanza","Champagne"],
    tonyWins: 4,
    tonyNominations: 13,
    wonBestMusical: true,
    performances: 1184,
    synopsis: "The winner of five Tony Awards, including Best Musical, In the Heights is a slice of urban life that tells the stories of various inhabitants of a barrio in Washington Heights, in the northern region of Manhattan. The community is populated by Dominican Americans and Nuyoricans who are all struggling to maintain their businesses and decide which traditions to maintain and which to leave behind.\n\nThe action centers on a bodega owned by Usnavi, a son of immigrants, who was named for the first sight his parents saw upon arriving in New York harbor: a U.S. Navy ship. The story focuses on several characters. Usnavi wishes to sell his bodega and return to his homeland, Stanford student Nina tries to reconcile the fact that she has lost her scholarship; she then falls in love with Benny, who works for her father’s automobile dispatch service. Abuela Claudia, the beloved neighborhood matriarch, dreams of winning the lottery and buys what turns out to be a winning ticket at Usnavi’s bodega. The relationships are thinly drawn and somewhat predictable, but the mundane story (described by one reviewer as “Spanish schmaltz”) was overwhelmed by the exhilarating music and dance sequences.\n\nIn the Heights was created in 1999 by Lin-Manuel Miranda when he was a college student at Wesleyan University. Two Wesleyan seniors, John Buffalo Mailer (son of novelist and playwright Norman Mailer) and Thomas Kail, helped him adapt the show for Broadway, with Kail serving as director and Miranda playing the central role of Usnavi.\n\nMiranda’s music and Andy Blankenbuehler’s choreography more than made up for the book’s deficiencies. The score, an invigorating blend of hip-hop, salsa, meringue, and soul, was vibrant and spirited. Using rap as a form of recitative was an ingenious development that helped make In the Heights popular with younger audiences. Similarly, the zesty dance routines kept things hopping throughout the production. The New York Times described the opening song as “among the most galvanizing opening numbers in recent Broadway memory.” Miranda played Usnavi throughout the show’s long run, but half of the key roles changed hands before the show finally closed after more than 1,100 performances.",
    themes: ["community","gentrification","immigration","home","the American Dream"],
    color: "#FF6B35",
