    composer: "Irving Berlin",
    lyricist: "Irving Berlin",
    bookWriter: "David Ives & Paul Blake Producers: Kevin McCollum, John Gore, Tom McGrath, Paul Blake, the Producing Office, Dan Markley, Sonny Everett, and Broadway Across America (John Gore: CEO; Thomas B. McGrath: Chairman; Beth Williams: COO & Head of Production); produced in association with Paramount Pictures Corporation",
    director: "Walter Bobbie",
    choreographer: "Randy Skinner",
    producer: "Kevin McCollum, John Gore, Tom McGrath, Paul Blake, the Producing Office, Dan Markley, Sonny Everett, and Broadway Across America (John Gore: CEO; Thomas B. McGrath: Chairman; Beth Williams: COO & Head of Production); produced in association with Paramount Pictures Corporation",
    notableCast: ["Stephen Bogardus","Jeffry Denman","Kerry O’Malley","Meredith Patterson","Charles Dean","Melody Hollis","Susan Mansur"],
    songs: ["Happy Holiday","White Christmas","Let Yourself Go","Love and the Weather","Sisters","The Best Things Happen When You’re Dancing","Snow","What Can You Do with a General?","Let Me Sing and I’m Happy","Count Your Blessings Instead of Sheep","Blue Skies","I Love a Piano","Falling Out of Love Can Be Fun","Love You Didn’t Do Right By Me","How Deep Is the Ocean","We’ll Follow the Old Man","I’ve Got My Love to Keep Me Warm"],
    performances: 53,
    synopsis: "Following the lead of Dr. Seuss’ How the Grinch Stole Christmas, this musical, based on the popular 1954 film version of White Christmas, returned for an encore run a year after it made its Broadway debut. The original film, which starred Bing Crosby, Danny Kaye, and Rosemary Clooney, had grown in stature in recent years, prompting the production of a stage version, which was presented on the increasingly family-oriented Broadway scene.\n\nThe musical version closely follows the plot of the film, with minor variances. After World War II, a general retires to run a winter inn in Vermont. When the lack of snow threatens the inn’s holiday season, two of the general’s former enlisted men, both of whom have become top entertainers, come to their superior’s rescue by bringing their musical revue to the inn. Most of the songs in the movie were retained, including the iconic title number, with other Berlin favorites added to the score, such as “I’ve Got My Love to Keep Me Warm” and “How Deep Is the Ocean.” The show had two successful limited runs during consecutive seasons at the Marquis Theatre. In the show’s second run, the leads were portrayed by James Clow, Tony Yazbeck, Mara Davi, Melissa Errico, David Ogden Stiers, and Ruth Williamson. Although critics were mainly impressed with Randy Skinner’s scintillating choreography, the New York Times acidly described the production as “fresh and appealing as a roll of Necco wafers found in a mothballed Christmas stocking.”",
