    director: "Bill T. Jones",
    choreographer: "Bill T. Jones",
    producer: "Shawn “Jay-Z” Carter, Will & Jada Pinkett Smith, Ruth and Stephen Hendel, Roy Gabay, Sony Pictures Entertainment, Edward Tyler Nahem, Slava Smolokowski, Ken Greiner and Chip Meyrelles, Douglas G. Smith, Steve Semlitz/ Cathy Glaser, Daryl Roth/ True Love Productions, Susan Dietz/ Mort Swinsky, and Knitting Factory Entertainment",
    notableCast: ["Sahr Ngaujah","Kevin Mambo","Saycon Sengbloh","Lillias White","Ismael Kouyaté","Gelan Lambert"],
    songs: ["Everything Scatter","Iba Orisa","Mr. Syms","Manteca","I Got the Feeling","Originality/ Yellow Fever","Trouble Sleep","Teacher Don’t Teach Me Nonsense","Lover","Upside Down","Expensive Shit","Pipeline","I.T.T. (International Thief Thief)","Water No Get Enemy","Egbe Mio","Zombie","Na Poi","Sorrow Tears and Blood","Iba Orisa/ Shakara","Rain"],
    performances: 463,
    synopsis: "This musical celebrates the life of Fela Anikulapo-Kuti, a Nigerian composer, musician, political activist, and pioneer of Afrobeat music. Formulating Afrobeat in the early 1960s, Fela took his music to the United States, where he became influenced by the American Black Power movement. After returning to Nigeria, he formed his own communal compound called the Kalakuta Republic and declared its independence from Nigeria. His music now focused on attacking Nigeria’s corrupt and oppressive military government, which inspired an attack on Fela and his family, during which Fela’s mother, a political activist herself, was killed.\n\nAlthough the show deals with events surrounding the 1977 invasion of the Kalakuta Republic, Fela! is dominated not by story, but by the pulsing music and irresistible rhythms of Afrobeat and Bill T. Jones’s scintillating choreography, which won a Tony Award. The character of Fela is onstage continuously, with the magnetic Sahr Ngaujah, who originated the role, playing five shows a week and alternate Kevin Mambo the other three. Fela! was the most original, refreshing, and different production to hit Broadway during the 2009 – 10 season, a show that the New York Times said “melts walls.”",
