    performances: 733,
    description: "A suburban mother battles bipolar disorder while her family struggles to hold together. The most emotionally unflinching examination of mental illness in musical theatre history.",
    funFact: "It won the Pulitzer Prize for Drama. Alice Ripley called performing the lead role eight times a week \"like running a marathon while crying.\"",
    synopsis: "The electroshock therapy that Alice Ripley receives in Next to Normal is exactly what the innovative musical brought to Broadway in 2009: a new and electrically charged concept that became a brilliant beacon in a season saturated with revivals, touristy stage adaptations of popular films, and little else. With no choreography to speak of, only six cast members, and a set that looked like it was left over from The Hollywood Squares game show, just about everything was different about this musical. Next to Normal’s plot is simple: a family falls apart while dealing with the mother’s battle with bipolar disorder. Central character Diana Goodman (Alice Ripley) goes through an emotional roller coaster during the show, which reflected the rising and falling moods of the story, as moments of humor are balanced with scenes of unspeakable pain, both physical and emotional. The result was the season’s biggest hit. The New York Times called it “something much more than a feel-good musical: it is a feel-everything musical.”\n\nNext to Normal was nominated for 11 Tony Awards, winning three, for Best Score, Best Orchestration, and Best Actress for Alice Ripley’s incandescent performance as the afflicted Diana. Although Tom Kitt’s music was scored for a small rock combo, the tasteful inclusion of acoustic guitar, violin, and cello helped attenuate the softer, sadder, more sensitive sequences in the script. The show won the Pulitzer Prize for Drama for 2010. Notable replacements during the show’s run included Marin Mazzie and Brian d’Arcy James.",
    themes: ["mental illness","family","grief","treatment","normalcy"],
