    bookWriter: "Chris D’Arienzo Producers: Matthew Weaver, Carl Levin, Jeff Davis, Barry Habib, Scott Prisand, Relativity Media, and Corner Store Fund; produced in association with Janet Billig Rich, Hillary Weaver, Toni Habib, Paula Davis, Simon and Stefany Bergson/ Jennifer Maloney, Charles Rolecek, Susanne Brook, Israel Wolfson, Sara Katz/Jayson Raitt, Max Gottlieb/ John Butler, David Kaufman/ Jay Franks, Michael Wittlin, Prospect Pictures, Laura Smith/ Bill Bodnar, Happy Walters, Michele Caro, and the Araca Group",
    director: "Kristin Hanggi",
    choreographer: "Kelly Devine",
    producer: "Matthew Weaver, Carl Levin, Jeff Davis, Barry Habib, Scott Prisand, Relativity Media, and Corner Store Fund; produced in association with Janet Billig Rich, Hillary Weaver, Toni Habib, Paula Davis, Simon and Stefany Bergson/ Jennifer Maloney, Charles Rolecek, Susanne Brook, Israel Wolfson, Sara Katz/Jayson Raitt, Max Gottlieb/ John Butler, David Kaufman/ Jay Franks, Michael Wittlin, Prospect Pictures, Laura Smith/ Bill Bodnar, Happy Walters, Michele Caro, and the Araca Group",
    notableCast: ["Constantine Maroulis","Amy Spanger","James Carpinello","Adam Dannheisser","Mitchell Jarvis","Michele Mais","Lauren Molina","Paul Schoeffler","Wesley Taylor"],
    songs: ["Cum On Feel the Noize","Just Like Paradise","Nothin’ But a Good Time","Sister Christian","We Built This City","Too Much on My Hands","I Wanna Rock","We’re Not Gonna Take It","More Than Words","Heaven","To Be with You","Waiting for a Girl Like You","Wanted Dead or Alive","Renegade","I Want to Know What Love Is","Harden My Heart","Shadows of the Night","Here I Go Again","The Final Countdown","Any Way You Want It"],
    synopsis: "This jukebox musical was a tribute to glam rock and heavy metal groups of the 1980s, with a book written by Chris D’Arienzo. The story takes place in 1987 on Hollywood’s Sunset Strip. The tossed tresses displayed in this show made the production of Hair, showing just down the street, seem like it needed a treatment of Rogaine.\n\nFortunately, however, Rock of Ages didn’t take itself too seriously, and the wit and self-mocking of the ’80s rock scene made for tremendously good fun. In the story, would-be actresses and guitar gods dream of fame while they hone their acts, which was pretty much what the ’80s were all about. The plot is no different than those of old Mickey Rooney/ Judy Garland musicals such as Babes in Arms: let’s save our nightclub from being shut down by the greedy German real estate developer. But because of the tongue-in-cheek, let’s-chuckle-at-what-we-thought-was-cool nostalgia of the show, it worked, whether or not you were familiar with black leather-and-denim groups such as Poison, Journey, Bon Jovi, and Twisted Sister. Production closed temporarily on January 9, 2011, to facilitate a move to the Helen Hayes Theatre, where it resumed performances on March 24, 2011.\n\nRock of Ages. Constantine Maroulis (as Drew Boley) wants to rock. (Joan Marcus)",
