    theatre: "Lunt-Fontanne Theatre",
    composer: "Andrew Lippa",
    lyricist: "Andrew Lippa",
    bookWriter: "Marshall Brickman, Rick Elice",
    director: "Jerry Zaks, Phelim McDermott",
    choreographer: "Sergio Trujillo",
    producer: "Stuart Oken, Roy Furman, Michael Leavitt, Five Cent Productions, Stephen Schuler, Decca Theatricals, Scott M. Delman, Stuart Ditsky, Terry Allen Kramer, Stephanie P. McClelland, James L. Nederlander, Eva Price, Jam Theatricals/ Mary Lu Roffe, Pittsburgh CLO/ Gutterman-Swinsky, Vivek Tiwary/ Gary Kaplan, the Weinstein Company/ Clarence, LLC, and Adam Zotovich/ Tribe Theatricals; produced by special arrangement with Elephant Eye Theatrical",
    notableCast: ["Nathan Lane","Bebe Neuwirth","Kevin Chamberlin","Jackie Hoffman","Zachary James","Adam Riegler","Krysta Rodriguez","Terrence Mann","Carolee Carmello","Wesley Taylor"],
    songs: ["The Addams Family Theme","When You’re an Addams","Pulled","Where Did We Go Wrong","One Normal Night","Morticia","What If?","Full Disclosure","Waiting","Just Around the Corner","The Moon and Me","Happy/ Sad","Crazier Than You","Let’s Not Talk About Anything Else but Love","In the Arms","Live Before We Die","Tango de Amor","Move Toward the Darkness","Not Today"],
    performances: 722,
    synopsis: "The creators of The Addams Family initially sought to focus on Charles Addams’s surreal New Yorker drawings for inspiration rather than the more accessible 1960s television sitcom. When the script was finally completed, however, it was the sitcom that won out, with the Broadway show including Vic Mizzy’s infectious finger-snapping theme song. Like the TV show, the Broadway version is a ghoulash of morbid jokes and unabashed sentimentality concerning the members of the eccentric family. Matriarch Morticia is afraid of growing old, teenaged Wednesday is concerned that her new, normal boyfriend Lucas is too different from her (a perverse Montague/ Capulet coupling), and bullet-headed Uncle Fester has fallen in love with the moon. By show’s end, everything is wrapped up in nice, tidy packages: Gomez and Morticia are tangoing again, Wednesday and Lucas are getting married, and Fester launches himself skyward with a rocket strapped to his back.\n\nAdding such Broadway scene stealers as Nathan Lane and Bebe Neuwirth made The Addams Family a surefire hit, despite a book that was described by the New Yorker itself as “an endless illustration of the family’s evident pathological characteristics.”\n\nThe story was nothing new, harkening back to nearly every episode of the television version, which often depicted an encounter between the members of the Addams clan and citizens of “normal” society. An undistinguished score by Andrew Lippa seemed to be the nail in the coffin for this production, but somehow, the show was a success, playing to sold-out audiences well into its second year. This was due in part to the presence of Lane, nostalgia for the show and its characters, a script that played well to children as well as adults, and an effective marketing campaign. Beginning March 22, 2011, Roger Rees replaced Nathan Lane as Gomez Addams.",
